<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Food, Bicycle Riding Link Bush with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Eating Chinese food and riding
a bicycle are nothing in particular for the Chinese, but seem to
symbolize a special feeling for former US President George Bush
about the most populous country in the world.
</P>
<P>
Bush, who served as head of the US Liaison Office in
Beijing from 1974 to 1975, became acquainted with China and its
people by tasting Chinese food and riding down streets and alleys
in Beijing on a bicycle. Even in his 1988-1992 presidential
tenure, Bush used to eat in Chinese restaurants.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five years have passed, and the 74-year-old Bush, who
has visited China each year since stepping down as president in
1992, still pays close attention to Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
Bush serves as honorary president of the China program of the
Volunteer Organization of America (VOA), which dispatches dozens
of US experts to China each year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Bush, together with former Chairman of the US Joint
Chiefs of Staff Colin Powell, supports another program concerning
personnel exchanges between China and the US, in which Chinese
scholars are invited to the US.
</P>
<P>
Bush, who came to Beijing this time for a seminar on the Asian
financial crisis held on Tuesday, told the seminar that China has
received real recognition both for its active engagement in
providing "tangible assistance" to help regional economies
recover, and for its willingness to made the "tough decision" not
to devalue its currency.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese economy will have a growing impact on
the global economy because of its size and growth rate, noting
that China's integration into the global economy will enable the
country to play an even greater role in terms of politics,
economy and security.
</P>
<P>
China has a lot of friends around the world, who praise China's
major role in dealing with the financial crisis, he said. "I am
one of them," he added. Bush wished China success in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is wise for the US to pursue a policy of active
engagement with China. He noted that a sound US-China
relationship is critical to world peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton's upcoming visit to China will "give a
strong push forward to the bilateral relationship," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bush said he believes that conducting more personnel exchanges
is very important for the promotion of mutual understanding between
the two influential countries with different social systems and
traditions.
</P>
<P>
The governments and non-governmental organizations of the two
countries should continue to make efforts in this area, he added.
</P>
<P>
Bush, a grandfather of 14, said that he hopes that his
grandchildren and Chinese children will live in a peaceful world
in the new century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
