<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Leader Calls for Regional Integration in Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- An ASEAN leader said here
Thursday that regional integration and cooperation are much needed
in pulling the battered Southeast Asian economies out of the
current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Rodolfo C. Severino, secretary-general of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), told an economic conference:
"Today's crises and challenges call for tighter integration,
closer cooperation and stronger solidarity in ASEAN."
</P>
<P>
Since ASEAN was founded 31 years ago, no disaster has hit the
Southeast Asian countries with such widespread impact as the
financial crisis, which first struck Thailand in July last year
and then spilled over to neighboring economies.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN has strongly reaffirmed its commitment to regional
economic integration and open regionalism," said the
secretary-general here Thursday at the Far Eastern Economic
Review's annual conference, adding that member countries are
continuing their efforts in building the ASEAN Free Trade Area,
which is now on the verge of completion.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, ASEAN countries have agreed to establish an economic
monitoring mechanism to keep track of capital flows and other
macroeconomic indicators and to use ASEAN currencies, instead of
hard currency, for the settlement of intra-ASEAN trade.
</P>
<P>
Saying today's challenge is that of globalization, the ASEAN
official stressed: "ASEAN's response to global challenges has to
be not greater national assertiveness, as countries might normally
have reacted in the past, but greater regional integration and
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
He finally pointed out that the effectiveness of ASEAN's
response to the new challenges depends to a large extent on
Indonesia, the largest country in Southeast Asia, where political
uncertainty still exists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
