<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts from Clinton's China Policy Speech At NGS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Following are excerpts from the
speech made by U.S. President Bill Clinton on China policies at
the National Geographic Society on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
As all of you know, I will go to China in two weeks' time. It
will be the first state visit by an American president this
decade. I'm going because I think it's the right thing to do for
our country.
</P>
<P>
Today I want to talk with you about our relationship with China
and how it fits into our broader concerns for the world of the
21st century and our concerns in particular for developments in
Asia. That relationship will, in large measure, help to determine
whether the new century is one of security, peace, and prosperity
for the American people.
</P>
<P>
Let me say that all of you know the dimensions, but I think it
is worth repeating a few of the facts about China. It is already
the most populous nation. It will increase by the size of
America's current population every 20 years. Its vast territory
borders 15 countries. It has one of the fastest-growing economies
on earth. It holds a permanent seat on the National Security
Council of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 25 years, it has entered a period of profound
change, emerging from isolation, turning a closed economy into an
engine for growth, increasing cooperation with the rest of the
world, raising the standard of living for hundreds of millions of
its citizens.
</P>
<P>
The role China chooses to play in preventing the spread of
weapons of mass destruction or encouraging it, in combating or
ignoring international crime and drug trafficking, in protecting
or degrading the environment, in tearing down or building up trade
barriers, in respecting or abusing human rights; in resolving
difficult situations in Asia, from the Indian subcontinent to the
Korean peninsula, or aggravating them; the role China chooses to
play will powerfully shape the next century.
</P>
<P>
A stable, open, prosperous China that assumes its
responsibilities for building a more peaceful world is clearly and
profoundly in our interests. On that point, all Americans agree.
But as we all know, there is serious disagreement over how best to
encourage the emergence of that kind of China and how to handle
our differences, especially over human rights, in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
Some Americans believe we should try to isolate and contain
China because of its undemocratic system and human-rights
violations, and in order to retard its capacity to become
America's next great enemy. Some believe increased commercial
dealings alone will inevitably lead to a more open, more
democratic China.
</P>
<P>
We have chosen a different course that I believe to be both
principled and pragmatic, expanding our areas of cooperation with
China, while dealing forthrightly with our differences. This
policy is supported by our key democratic allies in Asia; Japan,
South Korea, Australia, Thailand and the Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Get in Line With EURO II Emission Norms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Starting July 1, imported
vehicles with emission limits higher than accepted in the European
Union, will no longer be matriculated in Romania.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the drastic measures taken by the Romanian
government to reduce emission of nocivious substances.
</P>
<P>
At the first stage, the imported cars, either new cars or
second-hand ones, will have to meet EU norms of pollutant
emissions for the period 1995-1998, namely EURO II norms. Measures
concerning Romanian cars, of which 80 percent are Dacia brand,
will be gradually implemented.
</P>
<P>
The cars already in circulation will run with their current
emission level until January 1, 2000, when the Romanians will have
to set to their cars the Bosch pollution avoiding system in order
to line up with the EURO II norms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Takes Action Against Marine Pollution: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has taken various
steps to improve the marine environment for the past several years
and in future these efforts will continue, a Hong Kong official
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The work of enforcing legislation, building better environment
protection infrastructure and planning better to prevent pollution
will continue unabated," Secretary for Planning, Environment and
Lands Bowen Leung told an international conference.
</P>
<P>
"The sea is a major part of our life support system, not a sink
into which we can endlessly pour our waste without heed of
consequences," the official told the second International
Conference on Marine Pollution and Ecotoxicology at the City
University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
This is a truth which is relatively easy for Hong Kong, a city
built by the sea, to understand, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has already enacted the Dumping at Sea Ordinance to
prevent damage to the marine environment by dumping of waste into
local water, brought all of the coastal waters under the
comprehensive pollution controls provided by the Water Pollution
Control Ordinance, extended controls over livestock waste disposal
to cover the whole territory and built a sewage disposal
infrastructure, the official said.
</P>
<P>
With these measures, "we have seen significant improvements in
river quality and steady improvements in beach water conditions,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He admitted, however, marine water quality in Victoria Harbor
has continued to deteriorate, entrophication remains a serious
problem and pollution of local waters by toxic substance has
become a cause of increasing concern.
</P>
<P>
"Building up knowledge about these issues and about techniques
for assessing the risks in order to establish control policies is
a key part of the work we are now doing," Leung said.
</P>
<P>
The official revealed that Hong Kong and neighboring Guangdong
province on the Chinese mainland are working closely to study the
environmental problems in the Pearl River Delta region as a whole
and to plan for sounder, more effective environmental management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Meets Peruvian Military Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Chairman of China's Central
Military Commission Chi Haotian has said that the Chinese government
attaches importance to the development of its relations with Peru,
still takes an active attitude toward the future exchanges and
cooperation between the two armed forces, and will make active
efforts to this end.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who is also state councillor and defense minister, made
the remarks here today in a meeting with Nicolas Hermoza, president
of joint command of the armed forces and commanding general of the
army of Peru.
</P>
<P>
Chi expressed his appreciation for Hermoza's positive efforts
in the past for the development of Sino-Peruvian relations and the
relations between the armed forces of the two countries, as well
as satisfaction with the growth of such relations.
</P>
<P>
Chi also briefed the visitors on China's foreign and defense
policies.
</P>
<P>
Hermoza expressed his admiration for China's achievements since
reform and opening-up, and said that the Peruvian government has
placed great importance on the development of its relations with
China in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
He added that he believed that his visit would enhance the
mutual understanding and friendship between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
