<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Historical Trend on Healthy Growth of Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin had
a successful state visit to the United States last fall, marking
the advent of a new era in Sino-U.S. relations. Amidst the sound
and stable growth of Sino-U.S. relations, the U.S. House of
Representatives, disregarding the consistent stance of the Chinese
government and the commitment by every U.S. administration after
1972, approved a motion last Tuesday in which it required
President Bill Clinton during his upcoming China visit to impose
pressure on the country and force it to abandon non-peaceful means
for the liberation of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
This is not only a bold move which interferes in China's
internal affairs but also sets barriers against further developing
the improved Sino-U.S. relationship.
</P>
<P>
It goes without saying that the Taiwan issue, the most
important and sensitive problem in China-U.S. relations, will be
an unavoidable topic during the China-U.S. summit between Jiang
and Clinton due later this month.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Sino-U.S. Joint Statement signed by the two heads
of state at the previous Washington summit has already
demonstrated the basic stance of the two governments in this
regard. The Chinese side in the statement underlined that the key
to healthy and stable Sino-U.S. ties is to properly handle the
Taiwan issue in accordance with the three joint communiques signed
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The American side reiterated that the U.S. side adheres to "One
China" stand and observes the three communiques. President Clinton
and the U.S. government also clearly elaborated that the United
States did not support "Two Chinas" or "One China, One Taiwan",
nor the independence of Taiwan, or Taiwan's entry into the United
Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Modernization Attempt Commemorated  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- On this day 100 years ago, Emperor
Guangxu of the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), China's last feudal
dynasty, issued an edict starting the first modernization reform
in China's history.
</P>
<P>
Today crowds of visitors flocked to the Palace Museum to view
an exhibition marking the centennial of the 1898 Reform
Movement.
</P>
<P>
Liang Sili, son of Liang Qichao, one of the initiators of the
reform, also came to the exhibition with his wife.
</P>
<P>
Emperor Guangxu's edict, the petition the reformers submitted
to the emperor and many other related items on display are
original historical archives and relics.
</P>
<P>
"Look, this is the letter of appointment for my father issued
by Emperor Guangxu," Liang said to his wife.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the 19th century, young Emperor Guangxu appointed
Kang Youwei, Liang Qichao and other officials to important
positions to carry out all-round political, economic and cultural
reform in order to avert the national crisis in which China faced
being partitioned by Western imperialist powers.
</P>
<P>
"I was only five years old when my father died, and I am not
very familiar with that period of history," said Liang, who is now
an academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
He said, "My father's most profound influence on me was to
encourage me to strive to make China prosperous and strong, and
fear no dangers and difficulties."
</P>
<P>
The reform was carried out for only 103 days, until September
21, when Empress Dowager Cixi staged a palace coup. Emperor
Guangxu was put into house arrest, and many reformers were
arrested. Six noted "scholars" were executed, whereas Kang Youwei,
Liang Qichao and a few other reformers fled China and went into
exile in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Tax Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- China's people's courts at various
levels have finished trying 5,917 cases of tax evasion and
resistance, and sentenced 4,241 serious criminals, since the law
on the management of taxation was promulgated five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Luo Haocai, vice-president of the Supreme People's Court, said
here today that the people's courts have consistently taken the
crackdown on tax crimes as the major task over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
Cooperating with the taxation, procuratorial and public
security departments, the courts at various levels have launched
special campaigns to combat crimes on tax evasion and resistance,
as well as illicit issuing of value-added tax notices.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Supreme People's Court, the State General
Administration of Taxation, the Supreme People's Procuratorate and
the Ministry of Public Security have established a system of regular
meetings to exchange information to fight against tax crimes.
</P>
<P>
Luo said the people's courts actively accepted cases submitted
by the taxation organs on compulsory enforcement of delaying
payment of taxes and fines.
</P>
<P>
From 1995 to 1997, the courts accepted a total of 8,153
cases submitted by the taxation organs in this regard, involving a
sum of nearly 100 million yuan (about 12 million US dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress has decided to conduct a nationwide inspection of tax
collecting and management in July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
