<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution on Qomolangma Causes Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The pollution on the highest
mountain in the world, Mt. Qomolangma, which was brought about by
an increased number of tourists and mountain climbers, has caused
public concern.
</P>
<P>
This reporter paid a visit last month to the base camp some
5,200 m above sea level, finding that the place was littered with
plastic boxes, drink bottles and waste paper left by visitors,
despite the fact that a garbage station has been set up.
</P>
<P>
"The site was grassland in 1972, when I first came here. But
there isn't any grass now," Yu Liangpu, secretary general of the
China Mountaineering Association, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said that man has set foot on every corner of the earth and
his activities are inevitably re-shaping the environment.
</P>
<P>
More than 7,000 tourists, mountain climbers and scientists
visited Mt. Qomolangma last year.
</P>
<P>
Dobuje, deputy director of the Dingri County Administration
Bureau of the Qomolangma Nature Reserve, said that China has taken
measures to protect the environment in the region, and that he is
optismistic about the future.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, he recalled, the Tibet Autonomous Region set up
offices to oversee the environmental protection work around
Mt. Qomolangma, and the government has sent teams regularly to
collect rubbish left by climbers and tourists.
</P>
<P>
Last year, some 30 tons of garbage was moved down from the
mountain, he said, adding that "it is hard to find any rubbish on
the mountain itself now."
</P>
<P>
But he noted that oxygen bottles left at sites some 7,000 m
above sea level have not been disposed.
</P>
<P>
The local government is asking climbers to pay environmental
protection fees if they want to climb the mountain. In addition,
six core protection zones have been established where hunting and
tree felling are strictly forbidden.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Dobuje said that some rare animals, including
snow leopards, wolves and antelopes, have returned to the foot of
the mountain recently.
</P>
<P>
"One of the urgent tasks is to spread environmental protection
information among local residents and tourists," Dobuje said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
