<HEADLINE> Chinese Business Leader Confident of HK's Recovery (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese business leader
expressed here Thursday his confidence that Hong Kong would once
again sail through the current economic turbulence as it did
before.
</P>
<P>
Jing Shuping, chairman of the All-China Federation of Industry
and Commerce, said Thursday morning that Hong Kong will rebound
from the current Asian financial turmoil sooner than most of the
Asian countries due to its own advantages and its special
relations with China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the morning session of the fifth annual conference
of the Far Eastern Economic Review, Jing, who is also
vice-chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference, said Hong Kong will have a
brighter future but it will have to go through some kind of
adjustment as it did previously.
</P>
<P>
Jing noted that Hong Kong, like any other places in the world,
has not been immune to the financial turmoil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Jing, who first came to Hong Kong right after he graduated from
 college in 1939 and has been to the region many times since
then, said he has seen how Hong Kong rode out a number of troubles
 such as recession, stock market crashes and bank failures in the
past.
</P>
<P>
"The first quarter of this year saw a negative growth in Hong
Kong," Jing said. "This is also nothing new at all."
</P>
<P>
A similar situation arose in the mid-1970s and again in the
mid-1980s, not to speak of the earlier days, Jing recalled. But
Hong Kong was not down on its knees, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Like a man falling sick, Hong Kong, after making a painful
adjustment, including belt tightening, became healthier and
competitive again in the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
The reason that Hong Kong always has not only survived but also
pushed ahead lies in the people of Hong Kong, who are talented and
resilient, always ready to rise to challenges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Business Leader Confident of HK's Recovery (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Different from most of the Southeast Asian nations, here in
Hong Kong, most of its fundamentals are good, Jing said.
</P>
<P>
They include the institutional and regulatory framework, the
rule of law, the free market economy, good infrastructure and the
world's third largest foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
Above all, serving as an important bridge between China and the
rest of the world gives Hong Kong advantages not available to
others, Jing stressed.
</P>
<P>
Jing said that to deal with the financial turmoil in Asia and
ensure the success of China's further economic reform, the Chinese
government has set for this year the objectives of keeping the
nation's economic growth rate at 8 percent, the inflation rate at
less than 3 percent and the national currency RMB's exchange rate
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The three objectives combined are designed to keep China moving
on the track of "high growth, low inflation and progress with
stability."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has the advantage of extensive business and
information networks, which are extremely sensitive to customer
needs, market opportunities and the global trend of new and high
technology development.
</P>
<P>
It will thus be able to play a great role in helping the
Chinese mainland's overall economic development in the next five,
10 or 15 years, Jing said.
</P>
<P>
Jing noted that the current financial turmoil has a negative
impact on both the China's mainland and Hong Kong's economies
and the adjustment period will be even painful to many people who
are affected by the storm and the subsequent measures of reform
and adjustment.
</P>
<P>
"However, I firmly believe that China's mainland and Hong Kong
will zoom ahead like a jumbo jet irrespective of occasional
turbulence," Jing said to the dozens of local and foreign business
leaders present at the conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
