<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Historical Trend on Healthy Growth of Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese government has repeatedly announced its willingness
to reunify the country by peaceful means, but cannot undertake not
to use armed means to resolve the Taiwan issue. The stance of the
Chinese government in this regard is targeted at foreign
interference and so-called "Taiwan independence" instead of the
Taiwan people.
</P>
<P>
It is the set guideline for reunifying China by peaceful
means. However, every sovereign state has the right to take all
means it deems essential, including military means, to safeguard
its national sovereignty and territorial integration. On how to
handle its internal affairs, the Chinese government is not obliged
to make any commitment to any foreign country or any party,
especially those aiming to split China.
</P>
<P>
Many far-sighted people in the U.S. hold that Sino-US relations
would be stalled, and even see some setbacks if the Taiwan issue
is beset with troubles. Such a move is itself not in the realistic
and long-term interest of the U.S. They suggest that the U.S. look
squarely at China's position on the Taiwan question, effectively
observe the Sino-U.S. joint communiques and Sino-US Joint
Statement as well as the commitment made by the U.S. government,
so as to maintain the good momentum of development in Sino-US ties.
</P>
<P>
Only by dispelling all interference and uproar in Sino-US
relations can statesmen in both countries stand higher and see
farther in dealing with Sino-US relations, as a reformer in
China's Song Dynasty said in a poem: "Unafraid of floating clouds
blocking the view, because you stand at the pinnacle." And only by
grasping the fundamental interests of the people of both countries
and having an overall world situation in mind can a prosperous,
stable and peaceful world be properly brought into the 21st
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Announces Air Exercises in Albania, Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- NATO announced Thursday that it
would conduct air exercises as soon as possible in Albania and
Macedonia to demonstrate its ability to project power rapidly into
the region.
</P>
<P>
The air exercises were announced after NATO defense ministers
met for a whole day discussing a range of military options the
Western military alliance could take if Slobodan Milosevic
continued indiscriminate use of force against the civilian
population in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers gave the go-ahead to NATO military
authorities to conduct an appropriate air exercise both in Albania
and Macedonia as quickly as possible with the consent of the two
countries and with the aim of demonstrating NATO's capability to
project power rapidly into the region.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers also instructed NATO military authorities
to assess and develop as soon as possible a range of military
options for further consideration and decision by the North
Atlantic Council, the decision-making body of the 16-nation
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers council expressed deep concern at the
deteriorating situation in Kosovo and called upon all parties to
avoid actions which prolong the violence.
</P>
<P>
NATO continues to support, the defense ministers stated, a
political solution which brings an end to the violence, provides
an enhanced status for Kosovo, preserves the territorial integrity
of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and safeguards the human
and civil rights of all inhabitants of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers also decided to accelerate the provision
of advice mandated by NATO foreign ministers who met late last
month on possible support for the United Nations and athe
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe monitoring
activity and on possible NATO preventive deployment of troops in
Albania and Macedonia, both member countries of NATO's Partnership
for Peace program.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the day's council meeting said that NATO still
lacks a U.N. Security Council resolution as the legal basis for
its military presence in and around Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
