<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Announces National Agenda Against Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif announced Thursday that his government will confiscate all
the land given to feudal landlords by the British before the
partition.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling a national agenda against sanctions in a televised
speech Thursday evening, the prime minister said all the 1.2
million acres (about 486,000 hectares) of land to be confiscated
will be re-distributed among landless poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in Pakistan's history that the government
has decided to confiscate land from the landlords.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the various measures envisaged in the national
agenda to counter the economic sanctions imposed by the West after
the country's nuclear tests in late May.
</P>
<P>
"Time has come for us to stand on our own feet. We should end
our dependence on others," Sharif said, appealing to the people to
support the government's decision in the interest of the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are not afraid of any sanctions. We have been facing
sanctions for over 10 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has no other option but to go nuclear to defend
national security after the Indian nuclear tests, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has imposed a ban on the purchase of
everything for official and semi-official departments and the
government will not buy any new car, furniture, air conditioner
and other things.
</P>
<P>
The government expenditure will be cut by 50 percent in the
forthcoming budget for the next fiscal year, he said.
</P>
<P>
No foreign visit on public expense can be undertaken by any
government official without special permission from the prime
minister, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
No official function can be held in hotels without the
permission of the prime minister and the chief ministers, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the government will launch special
education programs to promote literacy in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Every child will get education in the next five years," he
declared.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he will move out from the grand Prime
Minister's House to a smaller one to save money.
</P>
<P>
He said all the houses of governors and chief ministers will be
converted into guest houses and all the governmental guest houses
will be sold out to pay the country's foreign debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
