<HEADLINE> IFC Approves 247 Mln Dlrs for S.Korea's Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) Thursday announced the approval of four
investments of 247 million U.S. dollars equivalent in South
Korea's financial sector, the first in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The four investments in loans and equity are designed to
enhance the country's private sector and are a mark of the IFC's
confidence in its economic recovery and long-term potential
development.
</P>
<P>
The approval of three new projects on June 9 and one new
project on May 28 marks a resumption in the IFC's investment
activity in South Korea for the first time in 10 years. The
investments are intended to attract other lenders and investors to
South Korea, either under the IFC's umbrella or through
co-investments.
</P>
<P>
The investments include: 25 million dollars in subordinated
convertible bonds of Korea Long Term Credit Bank (KLB), one of the
country's largest specialized banking institutions, a financing
package of 152 million dollars to Hana Bank to help build its
capital base and improve its foreign exchange liquidity and
financial guarantee for 40 percent of the Korea Trade Enhancement
Facility (KTEF) 100 million dollar exposure taken by Sumitomo Bank
Limited as well as 30 million dollars as venture capital in
support of long-term investments in small and medium-sized
enterprises in the country's technology sector.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group, fostering economic
growth in developing countries by financing private sector
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
