<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Students Defy Order to Return to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Students from institutes of higher
learning in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's second largest city, Thursday
defied a government order to return to classes, and continued
with demonstrations, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Their class boycott is aimed at pressing the government to
reopen the University of Zimbabwe and Harare Polytechnic which
were close last week following demonstrations against corruption
which degenerated into anarchy.
</P>
<P>
President of Zimbabwe National Students Union Hopewell Gumbo
told the news agency, ''we are not going to comply with the
ultimatum. The demonstrations will continue.''
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Deputy Minister of Higher Education and
Technology Sikhanyiso Ndlovu said students should return to
classes Thursday or face unspecified consequences.
</P>
<P>
''If students decide not to attend classes,'' he said, ''the
ministry will assume they are not interested in learning, and the
government will not stand idlely by while the situation
deteriorates.''
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hundreds of students from Masvingo Technical
College and Masvingo Teachers' College in south Zimbabwe Thursday
disrupted traffic during a demonstration to press for the
reopening of two institutions of higher learning closed by the
government in Harare. 
</P>
