<HEADLINE> Fightings Stopped on 2 Fronts: Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government
spokesperson announced here at 16:00 p.m. Thursday that fightings
on both Badme-Shiraro front and eastern border front around Bure
have stopped.
</P>
<P>
A news release issued by the office of the Ethiopian
government spokesperson said, ''Thursday, Eritrean forces had
made two attacks on an Ethiopia post around Bure on the
Afar-Eritrea border'' and ''the fighting has stopped.''
</P>
<P>
The news release said, ''the Eritreans had advanced with a
brigade (over 2,000 troops) who were completely defeated,''
adding that ''there are heavy casualties and many dead on the
Eritrean side.''
</P>
<P>
The news release also said, ''fighting is now also over in
Erde Mattios on the Badme-Shiraro front'' which broke out earlier
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said, ''Eritrean troops had attacked an Ethiopian post with
a large contingent which was annihilated.''
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vice-President P. Kagame of Rwanda and a group from
the United States arrived in Ethiopia for mediations between
Ethiopia and Eritrea, according to the Ethiopian government
spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia accepted the U.S.-Rwanda peace proposal on June 4,
1998. 
