<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Students Suspended for Boycotting Exams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,034 students
have vacated the state-run Sokoine University of Agriculture
(SUA) following an official suspension for their boycotting the
annual exams, an official of the administration said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The official, who asked not to be named, told Xinhua on a
telephone interview that peace came back to the campus in
Morogoro, some 200 kilometers west of Dar es Salaam in the
morning and the armed policemen, the well-known Field Force Unit
(FFU), withdrew.
</P>
<P>
The students at various degrees and fields were ordered out of
the SUA, which was founded in 1984 as the second largest
university in Tanzania, following their strike against the final
exams on claims that they were served with the results of their
course work very late, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I announce to all undergraduate students who boycotted
examinations from June 8 until today that you have been suspended
until further notice," a statement by the SUA Vice-Chancellor
Anselm Luoga said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An official report said that less than one hundred students
took part in the exams in SUA which accommodate 1,252
undergraduate and postgraduate students majored in farming,
forestry, veterinary medicine, environmental conservation, soil
science and etc.
</P>
<P>
It said that apart from the boycott, there has been several
destructive incidents on the campus where some female students
were beaten for writing the papers and a laboratory was
vandalized since Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some parents arrived at the SUA to collect their children and
the FFU personnel came to mount tight security while the SUA
administration met to try to find a way out for ending the
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
