<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Increase Pensions for Gurkha Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
decided to increase the pensions for former Gurkha soldiers who
served in the British army and their families, the British Embassy
here said in a press release Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The revised pensions with rises ranging from 23 to 51 percent
depending on rank, years of service and date of retirement will be
distributed from October 1998, the embassy said, adding that the
former Gurkha soldiers can get an increased pension from January
1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
There are 26,375 ex-Gurkhas and their families who are
receiving pensions worth 6.9 million British pounds (about 11
million U.S. dollars) every year from the British government, the
embassy said.
</P>
<P>
Many retired Gurkha soldiers are receiving as little as 24
pounds (38 dollars) per month while their British counterparts are
getting 475 pounds (760 dollars).
</P>
<P>
For the past four years, the ex-Gurkhas have been demanding
pension parity with their British counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Their other demands include the right to live and work in
Britain and pensions for those dismissed without pensions.
</P>
<P>
They have been pressing hard for their demands and have even
threatened to file a case at London courts.
</P>
<P>
The British army drafted Nepalese in 1816 under the Sugauli
Treaty signed between Nepal and the East India Company of Britain.
</P>
<P>
About 250,000 Nepalese soldiers fought during the First and
Second World Wars and 15,000 of them were killed, figures show.
</P>
<P>
Under a tripartite agreement reached in 1947 between Nepal,
India and Britain, the British and Indian armies can recruit
Nepalese, who have been popularly known as Gurkha soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 2,500 to 3,000 Nepalese are serving in the British
army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Still Needs U.N. Mandate to Act in Kosovo: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary George
Robertson hinted Thursday that NATO still needs a United Nations
resolution to go with its planned military presence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister told the press that he could not see why
NATO could not get a U.N. Security Council mandate but clarified
that the Western military alliance would not produce any timetable
for itself or for Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that NATO defense ministers were considering
"inevitable use of air power" to rein in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, however, Robertson told reporters that days
and not weeks is the timetable set out for Belgrade to stop its
indiscriminate use of force against the civilian population in
Kosovo or NATO may have to resort to military intervention to help
solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official, who asked not to be named, said earlier
Thursday that NATO defense ministers reached consensus on
inevitable military intervention to force Milosevic to stop his
action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
When asked what other military options NATO defense ministers
had considered during the day apart from possible air strikes
against Serbian military facilities in Kosovo, the British defense
secretary said that NATO did not rule in nor ruled out any option.
</P>
<P>
He cited no-fly zone, electronic warfare and humanitarian
manouver as other options discussed by the defense ministers
during their council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Robertson stressed that it would be "rash and foolish for
Milosevic" to slight international calls to refrain from abuse of
force and urged Belgrade to think again and change tactics.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether Milosevic's planned trip to Moscow had
anything to do with the announcement of only air exercises instead
of more drastic NATO actions, the British defense minister said
that it would be good for the Russians to be involved in the
peace-making process.
</P>
<P>
The Russians, he said, have been heavily engaged in the process
already.
</P>
<P>
Robertson said that what NATO defense ministers meant in their
message is an even-handedness by asking for an end of violence on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
But he said that there will be the eventual military back-up
for the diplomatic and economic pressure exerted on the parties in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Britain has initiated a draft resolution to work through the
U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
