<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Concerns over Angola's Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Mose Tjitendero, Chairman of the
Parliamentary Forum of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC), who doubles as Namibian Speaker, said here Thursday that
SADC concerns over the delay of Angola's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Tjitendero made the remarks after meeting the Angolan
President Eduardo dos Santos, and said that SADC members
concerned over the fact the the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol is not
fully observed.
</P>
<P>
He said that countries in the region consider peace in Angola
is the pre-condition for development in the region, adding that
the future of the region could not be bright without peace in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
The SADC countries urged the parties in Angola to observe the
peace protocol and bring peace to the land and the southern
African region as soon as possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SADC Parliamentary Forum headed by Tjitendero arrived in
Luanda Tuesday for a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1997, the forum is aimed at promoting
cooperation among members of the parliaments of the SADC member
countries. 
</P>
