<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Conduct Air Exercises in Albania, Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- NATO announced Thursday that it
would conduct air exercises as soon as possible in Albania and
Macedonia to demonstrate its ability to project power rapidly into
the region.
</P>
<P>
The air exercises were announced after NATO defense ministers
met for a whole day discussing a range of military options the
Western militaly alliance could take if Slobodan Milosevic
continued indiscriminate use of force against the civilian
population in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers gave the go-ahead to NATO military
authorities to conduct an appropriate air exercise both in Albania
and Macedonia as quickly as possible, probably within days, with
the aim of demonstrating NATO's capability to project power
rapidly into the region.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said after the defense
ministers council meeting that the alliance had already got the
consent from Albania and Macedonia for the air exercises which are
expected to be held "very soon."
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers also instructed NATO military authorities
to assess and develop as soon as possible a range of military
options for further consideration and decision by the North
Atlantic Council, the decision-making body of the 16-nation
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers council expressed deep concern at the
deteriorating situation in Kosovo and called upon all parties to
avoid actions which prolong the violence.
</P>
<P>
NATO continues to support, the defense ministers stated, a
political solution which brings an end to the violence, provides
an enhanced status for Kosovo, preserves the territorial integrity
of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and safeguards the human
and civil rights of all inhabitants of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers also decided to accelerate the provision
of advice mandated by NATO foreign ministers who met late last
month on possible support for the United Nations and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe monitoring
activity and on possible NATO preventive deployment of troops in
Albania and Macedonia, both member countries of NATO's Partnership
for Peace program.
</P>
<P>
Solana condemned the deteriorating situation in Kosovo and
urged both sides to refrain from violence.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's meeting, the NATO chief said, was to show that the
alliance was ready for action and action plans included possible
use of NATO air power.
</P>
<P>
When asked where is the point to which NATO air strikes will be
triggered, the alliance chief said that how to proceed will have
to depend on the development of the situation on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that NATO would not rule out the possibility of
eventual deployment of ground troops in Kosovo itself.
</P>
<P>
In a separate press briefing, U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said that most defense ministers agreed that a U.N. Security
Council or an Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
mandate would be desirable but a U.N. mandate is not "imperative."
</P>
<P>
But the American defense chief said that NATO did not want to
send out a wrong signal that it was supporting Kosovo
independence.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the Contact Group are to meet Friday
in London to study the development of the situation in Kosovo and
the planned actions by NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
