<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Announces Measures Against Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Thursday unveiled a package of austerity measures to
counter the economic sanctions imposed by the West against the
country for its nuclear tests following those of India last month.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address to the nation Thursday evening, Sharif
said he was presenting before the nation a portion of his agenda
of self-reliance, development and nation-building and change.
</P>
<P>
In reality, it is a sweeping agenda under which he wants to
bring about revolutionary changes in social, economic, judicial,
administrative, political fields and in fact in all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
Reminding the nation that the country's present system has
become obsolete and outdated, the prime minister called for basic
changes in this system.
</P>
<P>
"Time has come for us to stand on our own feet. We should end
our dependence on others," Sharif said, appealing to the people to
support the government's decision in the interest of the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are not afraid of any sanctions. We have been facing
sanctions for over 10 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has no other option but to go nuclear to defend
national security after the Indian nuclear tests, he said, adding,
"It is not an easy decision."
</P>
<P>
Unfolding the wide-ranging national agenda, the prime minister
said top priority will be given to the development of the
agricultural sector and full implementation of two previous land
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Under the agenda, 1.2 million acres (486,000 hectares) of land
illegally occupied and saved from the land reforms will be
retrieved for distribution among landless poor farmers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The measure also covers lands granted by British colonial
rulers to feudal landlords for their loyalty to the rulers and
treachery with the motherland, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said such lands have already been identified and he has
directed the federal and provincial governments to take over the
possession of such lands for immediate distribution.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in Pakistan's history that the government
has decided to confiscate land from the landlords.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has imposed a ban on the purchase of
everything for official and semi-official departments and the
government will not buy any new car, furniture, air conditioner
and other things.
</P>
<P>
The government expenditure will be cut by 50 percent in the
forthcoming budget for the next fiscal year, he said.
</P>
<P>
All the cabinet ministers will not draw their salaries in the
coming months and all the parliamentarians agreed to cut their pay
and allowances, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
No foreign visit on public expense can be undertaken by any
government official without special permission from the prime
minister, he said. And no official function can be held in hotels
without permission of the prime minister and the chief ministers.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he will move out of the grand Prime
Minister's house to save money and all the houses of governors and
chief ministers will be converted into guest houses and all the
governmental guest houses will be sold out to pay the country's
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
He said his family have decided to pay back their loans and for
this purpose they are handing over their assets to banks to
recover the loaned amount by selling them.
</P>
<P>
He gave a strong warning to tax evaders and those involved in
gas and electricity theft, saying their place would be the jail.
</P>
<P>
He gave a four-week period to loan defaulters to settle their
accounts with banks and after the period, the government will take
measures to recover these loans and in future no one would dare to
pocket loans obtained for business.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he also announced that the government will launch
special education programs to promote literacy in the country.
"Every child will get education in the next five years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani prime minister's national agenda was announced
two weeks after the country was provoked by neighboring rival
India to have detonated its own nuclear devices, triggering strong
condemnations and severe economic sanctions from Western countries
including the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here say the economy of Pakistan, which has just 1.2
billion U.S. dollars of foreign exchange reserves, will be hit
particularly hard by the sanctions as its depressed economy is too
dependent on foreign aid and loans.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to deal with the post-nuclear blast sanctions, the
Pakistani government has already imposed a six-month state of
emergency in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
