<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Supports Peace Efforts Toward Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy Thursday expressed his country's support for finding a
solution to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after his meeting here with his Cypriot
counterpart Ioannis Kasoulides, during which they discussed the
latest development of the Cyprus problem and bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy, who arrived here Wednesday night for a one-day
visit, pointed out, however, that Canada does not have a specific
role as a broker or any particular initiative.
</P>
<P>
"We are here to underline the importance of finding a way of
engaging in a dialog and developing a serious examination of the
issues," the Canadian minister said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern part of the island in the
aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process has remained deadlocked since last
summer when Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of a
U.N.-sponsored peace talks with President Glafcos Clerides in
protest against the European Union (EU) decision to open accession
talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has refused to attend the intercommunal talks unless
his breakaway entity in northern Cyprus is recognized and Cyprus
suspends its accession talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on President Clerides' proposal for the
island's demilitarization, Axworthy told reporters that
"certainly I think that would be a major step forward to
demilitarize and download the confrontation areas."
</P>
<P>
He said he also discussed the issue during a meeting Thursday
in the Turkish Cypriot-controlled northern part of Nicosia with
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
"There has to be a form of guarantee of security because of
the past history which perhaps the international community can
provide," he added.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kasoulides described his meeting with Axworthy as
"productive and interesting" and expressed appreciation for the
Canadian minister interest in Cyprus, its problem and efforts
toward its resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Set Tight Budget: Nyachae </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae presented Thursday to parliament the 1998/99 budget aimed
at reviving the country's battled economy but also sending a
signal of an belt-tightening area.
</P>
<P>
The budget for the fiscal year of 1998/99 (July 1/June 30) is
focusing on cutting public spending especially on civil servants
wages and raising taxes with a view to curbing domestic debt,
interest rates, and finally the mounting budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
"The 1998/99 budget... reflects two principles that can be
summarized in a few words -- fiscal restraint and a balanced
budget," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am asking all of you to tighten your belts so that we can
achieve a balanced budget this year and thereafter achieve
surpluses," Nyachae said.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth in the east African country fell from 4.6
percent in 1996 to 2.3 percent last year. Analysts say the
darkest shadow brooding over the economy is that of the national
debt estimated currently at 160 billion Shillings (2.67 billion
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nyachae also vowed in the draft budget to speed up
privatization, enforce the tax system, cut governmental borrowing
requirements by at least five percent, improve infrastructure
especially roads and keep inflation within the single digit
level.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts to fight corruption and tax evasion will be
intensified," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, "expenditure will bear most of the required
adjustments," he announced, targeting that "a total expenditure
of 12,087.1 million Shillings (2 billion Dollars) will have to be
financed in 1998/99 fiscal year."
</P>
<P>
"The combined public sector wage bill, assuming civil servants
are given similar increment, would absorb 67 percent of total
revenue," he warned.
</P>
<P>
He asked for an additional reduction of 59,000 civil servants
over the next three years and renegotiating the Teachers Pay
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
"It will be necessary to freeze pay adjustments in 1998/99 for
all categories of public service, except for normal annual grade
increment of about four percent," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he proposed a series of taxation proposals with a
target that "ordinary revenues, mainly from taxes, will be
maintained at or below 24 percent of GDP."
</P>
<P>
The measures include raising the penalty of uncustomed goods,
raising the duty rate on a selected range of processed
agricultural produce and their substitutes, and strengthening the
fight against goods dumping on local markets.
</P>
<P>
The budget is announced after Kenya's tourism earnings is down
and the country has been hard hit by the El Nino weather pattern,
resulting in the decrease in agricultural output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
