<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortality Rates of Iraqi Children, Elderly Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Death toll among children under
five years and elderly people over 50 is still heavy, according
to the latest statistics released by Iraqi health ministry.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that in May, 4,897 deaths were recorded
among children under five years old, of whom nearly 2,000 died of
malnutrition, compared to 347 infant deaths in May 1989 before the
U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
As for the elderly people aged over fifty, the statistics show
that 2,443 death cases over the same period were registered, of
which 706 caused by hypertension, 307 by diabetes and 1,430 by
cancer. In May 1989, only 533 death cases were recorded.
</P>
<P>
The ministry put the blame on sanctions-spawned dearth in
food, medicine and other essentials of life.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive sanctions were imposed by the United Nations
in 1990 to punish Iraq's invasion of Kuwait. They can only be
lifted when U.N. inspectors verify that the country is free of
weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
