<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Down due to Monetary Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Romania's economy is still
unfunctional and price increases are avoided although the
inflation rate is down thanks to restrictive money policies
pursued by the National Bank, said economic analysts here.
</P>
<P>
The National Board on Statistics recently said the inflation
rate was 2.3 percent in May, lower than that in the previous
month. "May inflation figures came as no surprise in view of the
concerted policies of the National Bank and the Finance Ministry
aimed at keeping price increases at bay by sucking up the national
currency lei from the market and issuing T-bond for individual
savers," said economic analyst Ilie Serbanescu, former minister of
reform.
</P>
<P>
"Taking the figures as a yardstick, Romania is sitting pretty,
yet what is worrying is that the decrease in the inflation rate is
a mere facade and was caused by a falling consumption rate and
lower profit margins for the commercial companies," said Gabriela
Sendroiu, analyzing director for Romania of the Austrian
Creditanstalt group.
</P>
<P>
The government has projected a 2 percent monthly inflation rate
for the next period, which Serbanescu believes is realistic for
the summer months only. He said, "The problem is that more dangers
will add up in autumn: the skid of wage benefits if the
government gives way under social pressure; the recoupling of
money economy with real economy after the National Bank gave up
its policy of attracting deposits from commercial banks and thus
obliged them to use their liquidities to relaunch credit
operations."
</P>
<P>
"To ease inflation is the priority of the National Bank.
Romania will be lost if it does not win the war against
inflation," stressed Adrian Vasilescu, director of the bank's
Communication Department. "Some say that Romania should play an
inflation game. I reply that their theories come from old books
and do not apply to our times. Presently, the global economy
operates in an environment of low inflation. Keeping Romania on an
inflationary peak will prove catastrophic. If our policies were
changed right now, we would be taking too great a risk," Vasilescu
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
