<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government and the European Investment
Bank (EIB) Thursday signed two agreements, under which the EIB
will provide the kingdom with loans of 83 million ECU (about 91.3
million U.S. dollars) to fund water and potash production projects
in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Forty million ECU (44 million dollars) will be used to finance
the restructuring and rehabilitating of the drinking water
distribution network in Amman, Jordan's official news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The rest is to finance the expansion project of the Arab Potash
Company to help it increase production capacity from 1.8 million
tonnes of potash per year to 2.11 million tonnes.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The oil price slump caused 6.8 billion U.S. dollars of
economic losses to the Arab Gulf countries in the first quarter of
this year, Arab economists said in a report published by
Thursday's Al-Alam Al-Youm newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The oil price went down by six U.S. dollars per barrel during
that period.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- A 250 million-dollar financing contract was signed
in Dubai Thursday between the United Arab Navigation Company on
one side and the International Gulf Bank, the Arab Banking
Establishment and the National Bank of Kuwait on the other.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Arab Emirates (UAE) news agency, the
loan will be used to cover part of the 660 million-dollar contract
between the company and a Japanese ship-building group to build
ten new ships for the company.
</P>
<P>
Each of the ships will have a capacity of carrying 3,800
standard containers with a speed of 24 knots.
</P>
<P>
The remaining cost, namely, 410 million dollars, will be self
financed by the company. By signing this contract, the company
aims to enhance and develop operation services.
</P>
<P>
The company, owned by some Arab states including the UAE,
currently owns and operates 51 ships. The company services cover
most world trade to the Gulf and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Petroleum Cooperation Committee of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) member states will meet next Tuesday in
Riyadh to assess and support the Amsterdam oil accord,
well-informed petroleum sources announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The sources pointed out that the meeting is aimed at making a
comprehensive assessment of the agreement reached by Saudi Arabia,
Venezuela and Mexico on June 4 in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, on
cutting their oil production by 450,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf countries will support and back this accord at the
forthcoming conference of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) due to take place on June 24 in Vienna, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also consider at its one-day meeting
regional cooperation among the GCC states in petroleum industry,
and coordination of their stances regarding developments in the
world oil markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
