<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: U.S. Right Ring's Cold War Rhetoric </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- As President Bill Clinton is
preparing his visit to China later this month, right-ring
politicians in Congress are gathering things to create a "Chinese
plot" and whipping up a new China scare.
</P>
<P>
Among the sins being blamed on China are campaign
contributions, exploding satellite missiles, and the lease of a
shipping terminal in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
But as a Chinese philosophical concept goes, things turn into
their opposites when they reach the extreme. The "Chinese plot"
seems untrue to knowledgeable people, who also become skeptical of
the politicians' intentions of making a big deal out of nothing.
</P>
<P>
Columnist Robert Scheer called GOP's China card a "red joker."
In an article on Los Angeles Times Tuesday, he said that "on the
question of missiles, congressional partisans whip up a bogus
storm over a nonissue."
</P>
<P>
"There's no Clinton administration culpability or threat to
national security, despite lurid claims by Republicans," said
Scheer, citing an article written jointly by George Bush's
national security advisor Brent Scowcroft and undersecretary of
state Arnold R. Kanter. The two former officials said that the
Chinese government never requested information or other assistance
from the U.S. government to improve the space boosters they use to
launch satellites.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese do not need U.S. expertise to be able to hit an
American city with a nuclear-armed missile," Scheer wrote. "They
were already quite expert at rock technology back in 1988, when
Ronald Reagan authorized the launching of made-in-America
satellites atop Chinese rockets."
</P>
<P>
In all, he said, there was no Chinese plot to get the Clinton
administration to help Beijing with its rockets. In fact, "the
attempt by Republicans to make a big deal out of military
technology transfers to China is pathetically partisan and wholly
bogus. It represents a desperate recycling of Cold War rhetoric
that riles old fears but denies the new world reality."
</P>
<P>
This Cold War concept was shared by Ames O. Goldborough, who
wrote an article on San Diego Union Tribune on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing all the things conservatives in Congress used to blame
on China, Goldborough said that "ninety percent of this feigned
hysteria about China is political and the rest is the right wing's
frustration over America's lack of enemies."
</P>
<P>
The author made his point with the Long Beach-China Ocean
Shipping Company (COSCO) affair. When the Navy recently vacated
its base and shipyard in Long Beach, Southern California, the Port
of Long Beach decided to turn them into a cargo terminal. And part
of the new terminal would be leased to COSCO. But some House
conservatives decided the nation could not have Communists at a
former Navy base, although such officials as the defense
secretary, the navy secretary and the national security adviser
all assured them that COSCO, which operates in 36 U.S. ports, was
no threat to America's national security.
</P>
<P>
"It's tough to give up the Cold War when you've had it all your
life," said Goldrorough, as if there is nothing he could do about
it.
</P>
<P>
But he is sure that "despite our differences, the United States
and China can create friendly and cooperative post-Cold War
relations, as we are doing" and that "we shouldn't allow it to be
undermined by a handful of partisan politicians and Sinophobes
nostalgic for the Cold War."
</P>
<P>
Said Scheer in his article: "The Cold War is over and those who
now attempt to use fear of China to smear Clinton are lost in
time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi Can Benefit From Mozambican Corridors: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Malawi can greatly benefit from
using the economic potential of Mozambvique's Nacala and Sena
Development Corridors, a visiting Mozambican official told the
Malawi News Agency MANA Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's Beira Vorridor's Project Manager, Samuel Geza
said in Malawi's capital Lilongwe Thursday that the two corridors
would among other benefits "offer Malawi a vital transport leeway
taking into account Malawi is a land-locked country."
</P>
<P>
Malawi has for long relied on Mozambican port facilities of
Beira, Nacala and Maputo for her external trade, MANA reported in
a dispatch sent to Xinhua based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
However, reliance on the ports was further dealt a severe blow
when movement on the rail lines linking the two friendly nations
was halted by the historical 16-year Mozambican civil war that
had devastated much of the lines.
</P>
<P>
The rail lines have since been reopened.
</P>
<P>
Geza feels Malawi should as well, take advantage of the Nacala
and Sena development corridors' partially tapped potential in the
areas of tourism, mineral resource development, infrastructure
development and manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
The corridors, if fully utilized, said the Mozambican
official, could create employment opportunities for both
countries currently facing high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Geza is in Malawi as part of the delegation of investors from
the "special development initiative group" based in South Africa,
making a follow-up to Malawi's President Bakill Muluzi's visit to
South Africa last week that was also meant to discuss business
opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
