<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Inspector Urges Iraq's Continued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Richard Butler, executive chairman
of the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM,
said Thursday he hoped Iraq would continue to cooperate in getting
the UNSCOM's "small remaining job" done.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who arrived here Thursday, said at a press conference
that he would meet with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
this weekend to discuss what Iraq should do to show it has met all
the requirements under the relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that we will be able to agree in our forthcoming talks
on the steps we can take together that will enable me to enter
that report (October report), saying Iraq has taken all the
actions that are required of it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said if Iraq provides all information and materials that the
UNSCOM needs, his bi-annual report due to be presented to the
Security Council in October would be "very different from many
previous reports."
</P>
<P>
When asked about the possibility of conducting new visits to
Iraq's presidential sites, the chairman replied that the UNSCOM
has no such plans at the present time.
</P>
<P>
On the so-called road map the UNSCOM has drawn for Iraq, Butler
said "every item on the list of road map is well known to Iraq,
the materials involved we believe do exist. It is a clarifying
list, it is very concrete, it is the remaining things that are
needed to be done."
</P>
<P>
"I think both sides want to get it done. We have not come to
impose some lists on Iraq," he added.
</P>
<P>
Butler said Iraq has not given adequate information to the
UNSCOM with respect to its biological program, adding Baghdad had
provided clearer account on its missile and chemical programs.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the long time that the UNSCOM spent on
disarmament in Iraq to several reasons, including Iraq's earlier
attempt to conceal the existence of biological weapons and the
difficulties the UNSCOM is facing to complete its disarmament job.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that a big job remains for the UNSCOM to do, which
is to take some time. "What remains now is relatively small. With
Iraq's full cooperation, we can get this relatively small
remaining job done, I hope in a very short time, and the so-call
road map lists those things that we need to do to get that job
done," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief inspector noted that Iraq has promised
cooperation to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and had kept the
promise in every respect so far. He expressed hope that Iraq would
continue to be cooperative.
</P>
<P>
"I earnestly hope they keep it in this respect on this
weekend, and if they do, they will find we are absolutely
cooperative and competent to verify what they have shown us or
given us, and we'll get the job over very quickly," said Butler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
