<HEADLINE> UK Scheme to Infiltrate Industry, Win in World Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A new scheme which aims to place
young overseas professionals with UK companies was jointly
launched here Thursday by the Department of Trade and Industry and
the British Council.
</P>
<P>
The idea of the British Overseas Industrial Placement (BOND)
scheme is that these young overseas professionals will return to
their own country and give contracts and opportunities to their UK
host company.
</P>
<P>
According to the scheme, in the first year, it will focus on
the key sectors of oil, gas and petrochemicals, healthcare, power
generation, telecoms, environmental services, construction and
food &AMP; drink.
</P>
<P>
Initially it will concentrate on the following countries:
China, India, Pakistan, South Africa, Vietnam, Argentina, Brazil,
the Philippines, Malaysia, Thailand, Egypt and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching of the scheme, Minister for Trade
Lord Clinton Davis said, "Providing overseas professionals with
knowledge of, and contracts in, the UK has clear long-term
commercial benefits for Britain."
</P>
<P>
"Equally there can also be clear long term benefits for British
business. The placements will help to establish lasting
relations," he added. 
</P>
