<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Hails Russia's Position on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Thursday expressed welcome
to Russia's position on the protracted Cyprus problem that the
current impasse on the island has nothing to do with the
Cyprus-Russia missile contract.
</P>
<P>
A Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman stressed Wednesday that
"we are convinced that the reason for the deadlock in efforts for
a solution to the Cyprus problem is not the contract for the S-300
(missiles) but the maintenance of the unacceptable status quo on
the island."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was responding to foreign press reports on the
deployment of the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"The Republic of Cyprus has the undeniable sovereign right to
have the exclusive responsibility for its own defenses, since it
is a victim of international law violations due to the Turkish
invasion and occupation of a part of its territory," the spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the statements, Cypriot government spokesman
Christos Stylianides described them as "a correct position," a
view that Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides had also expressed.
</P>
<P>
The statements "reaffirm the solid position of the Cypriot
government that the issue of its defense is an exclusive right of
the Republic of Cyprus, something it exercises on a daily basis
because of the maintenance of the unacceptable status quo,"
Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides reiterated that the Cypriot government will only
cancel the deployment of S-300 defense system if considerable
progress is made toward a comprehensive Cyprus settlement or an
agreement for the island's demilitarization is reached.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered S-300 surface-to-air missiles
from Russia in January 1997. They are expected to be delivered in
mid-August this year.
</P>
<P>
The deal was opposed by countries including the U.S. and
Britain, while Turkey has threatened to strike the missiles if
they are deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the threats made by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash Wednesday, Stylianides said the Cypriot government "does
not accept any blackmail from Rauf Denktash."
</P>
<P>
Denktash told journalists in Istanbul, Turkey Wednesday that
"we will announce that the Cyprus problem is closed and invite
Turkey to fully establish itself in the northern part of the
island" if Russian missiles are delivered.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said that the Cypriot government will exercise its
foreign policy for the benefit of all Cypriots, reiterating that
Denktash's threats "will in no way affect the Cyprus Republic's
sovereign rights."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
