<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda: New Budget Presented to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Finance Minister Gerald
Ssendaula presented the budget for 1998/1999 fiscal year to
parliament Thursday afternoon, with emphasis on security,
education, roads, poverty eradication and pay reforms.
</P>
<P>
In his budget speech delivered at the Conference Center in
Nile Hotel, Ssendaula said that the new budget is aimed at
promoting rapid economic growth targeted at seven percent real
gross domestic product growth and poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
According to the new budget, spendings for the five priority
sectors will be increased at different rates.
</P>
<P>
Education spending will increase 49 percent to 253 billion
Uganda Shillings (253 million U.S. Dollars), the highest increase
rate among the five sectors, closely followed by security with
164 billion Shillings (164 million Dollars), an increase of 26
percent.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that education has been neglected
over the past few years. The new budget will enable the number
of primary school teachers to be increased by 20,000 from the
level in 1997 when free primary education was introduced.
</P>
<P>
The security situation in the northern and western regions,
which have been plagued by brutal rebel attacks on civilians,
necessitates a one-off increase in defense spending of 26
percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
The budget is also characterized by a 4-million-U.S.-Dollar
increase for road construction and a five percent pay increase
for civil servants.
</P>
<P>
In explaining the budget, the minister said that emphasis is
put on some areas instead of touching each sector as they had
done before.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, the development and recurrent
expenditures will remain at the previous level in the coming
fiscal year which begins from July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
