<HEADLINE> Turkey Suspends Arms Deal With France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has suspended an arms deal
worth 145 million U.S. dollars with France under the impact of the
recent political tension between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Necati Utkan said a meeting between
the defense industries of the two countries could not be held on
Turkey's purchase of Eryx antitank missiles from France's
Aerospatial due to the negative process witnessed in the
Franco-Turkish ties.
</P>
<P>
This was just one of the deals Turkey reportedly put on hold
because of the political tension triggered by a French
parliamentary bill approved on May 30 to recognize historical
claims of an Armenian genocide in 1915 by Turks.
</P>
<P>
On June 4, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel sent a letter to
his French counterpart Jacques Chirac, asking him to use his power
to correct French legislature's decision on the alleged Armenian
genocide.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has denied that the deaths of some 1.5 million
Armenians in Ottoman Turkey between 1915 and 1923 constituted a
genocide, insisting that massacres occurred on both sides as the
result of a civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
