<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Economic Growth Expected at 3.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DODOMA, Tanzania, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's economic
growth rate in the 1997-98 fiscal year is expected to arrive at
3.5 percent, below the target of 4.5 percent, Finance Minister
Daniel Yona said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the budget session of parliament in the new capital
of Dodoma in central Tanzania, Yona said the growth rate leaves
much to be desired, particularly when compared with an annual
population growth rate of 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This means that the real increase in per capita income of
Tanzanians is less than one percent," he told members of
parliament and foreign envoys at the two-month session which
began Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister also predicted that the country's revenue
collection for the whole year from July 1, 1997 to the end of
this month will reach 627,500 million Tanzanian Shillings (about
946 million U.S. Dollars), about 10 percent below the target of
678,000 million Shillings.
</P>
<P>
The slower economic growth and lack of revenue collection were
mainly attributed to the El Nino-charged heavy rains which have
destroyed key cash crops and severely damaged much of Tanzania's
transport infrastructures, causing long delays in moving exports
and imports, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for spendings, Yona said the total expenditures for the
year is likely to reach 866,951 million Shillings, 11 percent
less than the budget estimates consistent with resource
availability.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the developments in financial sector, he said the
Bank of Tanzania has effectively managed to control money supply
and inflation by using market-oriented policies.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the inflation rate, which reached 13.5 percent
by the end of April, is expected to fall to 10 percent by the end
of June.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the budget plans for the 1998-99 fiscal year, Yona
said the government plans to collect 695,165.9 million Shillings
from its domestic sources and spend 1,007,786 million Shillings.
The government will cover the budget deficit from domestic
sources, external assistance and various revenue measures.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that the budget frame for the year
1998-99 has been prepared with a view to achieving a gross
domestic product (GDP) growth rate of 3.5 percent and keeping
down inflation rate to 7.5 percent by the end of June, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
