<HEADLINE> U.S. Humanitarian Aid Plane Flies to Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A plane loaded with 1 million
U.S. dollars worth of aid from the Catholic Church took off from
Fort Lauderdale, Florida, and flew directly to Cuba in nearly two
years.
</P>
<P>
The flight, which will ship medical facilities, food and other
humanitarian aid directly to Cuba, is the first since the Clinton
administration eased restrictions on flights in March.
</P>
<P>
The aid was to be delivered to the Cuban Catholic Church's
charity arm Caritas Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Washington suspended direct flights for Cuba after Cuban air
force jets shot down two Cuban exile planes in the Florida Straits
in February 1996, killing four people.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration also allowed Cubans in the U.S. to
post cash to their relatives in Cuba and approved faster
procedures for medical sales. The measures marked changes in the
36-year-old U.S. embargo against Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
