<HEADLINE> Turkey Offers Assistance to Solve Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem has offered assistance to solve the Kosovo issue in a letter
sent to his British counterpart Robin Cook, a government spokesman
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry Spokesman Necati Utkan said at a
weekly press briefing here that Cem briefed Cook on the results of
the meeting of the Balkan Foreign Ministers, held on June 8-9 in
Turkish largest city Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Cem offered Turkish assistance to Cook, who will
host the Contact Group meeting in London on Friday, on solving the
Kosovo conflict, he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about Turkey's position in case of the intervention
by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, of which Turkey is a
member, Utkan said that "Turkey would bring its own contributions
within the ideas in NATO in case of such an intervention."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question if Turkey would impose political
sanctions on Yugoslavia like some other countries, the spokesman
declined a direct answer, saying the measures that each country
would take will be different.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish Foreign Ministry statement issued Thursday said that
Turkey hopes that closer contact will be established between the
regional countries and the Contact Group.
</P>
<P>
"To this end, we have expressed our wish to establish a
mechanism that would provide a powerful flow of information," the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo issue has been worsening since last February when
bloody clashes erupted between Serbian police and ethnic
Albanians who demand independence from Belgrade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
