<HEADLINE> Uganda to Reduce Duty Rates on Fuel, Drinks: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has decided to reduce the
duty rates on fuel as well as drinks to boost sales of these
products in the country, Finance Minister Gerald Ssendaula said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ssendaula said this in his new budget speech to members of
parliament Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to his budget speech, fuel duty rate will be reduced
by 30 Uganda Shillings per liter for petrol and household
kerosene while that for diesel will drop by 60 Shillings per
liter.
</P>
<P>
"Tax reductions will benefit consumers," Ssendaula said. "I
have decided to make further modest reductions in the excise duty
rates for beer and sodas."
</P>
<P>
"For beer, the excise rate is being reduced from 65 percent to
60 percent and for soft drinks, the reduction is from 30 percent
to 25 percent," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The basis for making these reductions is that higher sales
will also produce bigger revenues, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ssendaula said that the measures will take effect from the
midnight. At present, about 1,150 Uganda Shillings equal to one
U.S. Dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
