<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland Supports U.N. Efforts for Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Finland supports U.N. efforts in
reaching a peaceful Cyprus solution and the island's course for
European Union (EU) accession, a Finnish envoy said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jaakko Blomberg, special representative of Finland for Cyprus,
was speaking to reporters following a meeting with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
He said his visit here is aimed at preparing for Finland's turn
of EU six-month rotating presidency due to start on July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"For Finland, the question of Cyprus has two basic meanings,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
These, he explained, are the U.N. framework for a peaceful
Cyprus settlement and the EU context for Cyprus' accession
process, both of which Finland is supporting.
</P>
<P>
He noted, however, that the two courses "affect each other." If
a settlement is not reached before the accession, the EU "will
then have to decide its position with the view to the accession of
Cyprus," he added.
</P>
<P>
Blomberg pointed out that a solution under the U.N. aegis
would facilitate the accession of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish envoy also expressed the hope that U.N.-led Cyprus
peace talks will soon be resumed and the Turkish Cypriot community
will finally be represented in the accession negotiations, which
Cyprus started in March with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace process came to a standstill last summer when
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of a
U.N.-sponsored peace negotiations with Greek Cypriot leader,
President Glafcos Clerides, in protest against an EU decision to
open accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said he would not return to the negotiating table
unless his breakaway entity in northern Cyprus controlled by the
Turkish Cypriots is recognized and the Cypriot government
suspends accession talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed its troops and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking
union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
