<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Votes on Campaign Finance Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Acting on the first of many
votes on highly controversial campaign finance legislation, the
U.S. House of Representatives Thursday rejected a proposed
constitutional amendment that would have given Congress and the
states power to restrict campaign spending and contributions.
</P>
<P>
The House voted 345-29 against the proposal, which required a
two-thirds majority vote for passage. Fifty-one Democrats voted
"present," but took no position on the measure.
</P>
<P>
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, a Republican, who voted against
the proposal, said he offered it for a vote to show that pending
proposals would actually limit Americans' right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
Such an amendment, he argued, would be needed to enact any of
the 11 reform proposals awaiting consideration because the Supreme
Court has equated spending with political speech.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of reform criticized opponents of distorting the
issue.
</P>
<P>
"Every time the anti-reformers say `free speech,' they really
mean big money," said Rep. Tom Allen, a Democrat and sponsor of a
popular reform bill drafted by freshman class members.
</P>
<P>
Representative Barney Frank, a Democrat, said Delay was "for
free speech as long as it is expensive."
</P>
<P>
House Democrats' leader Dick Gephardt, who has accused
Republicans of delaying campaign finance legislation, urged
Democrats to withhold support for the amendment and to vote for a
leading reform bill sponsored by Representatives Christopher
Shays, a Republican, and Marty Meehan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, which would ban so-called "soft money," -- the
unregulated donations to national and state political parties from
corporations, labor unions and individuals, and regulate issue
advertising by third parties and expand disclosure requirements,
will be debated at a later date. The bill, which is supported by
U.S. President Bill Clinton, is similar to reform legislation that
died in the Senate last year.
</P>
<P>
The competing proposal by first-term members would "ban soft"
money only at the federal level, increase contribution limits and
require additional disclosure by outside groups.
</P>
<P>
Debate on campaign finance reform is expected to drag on for
weeks as House Republican leaders, who oppose the bill, have
approved several hundred possible amendments to the 11 reform
proposals.
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders attempted to suppress the issue earlier this
year, but agreed to a second round of debate after falling under
intense pressure from a handful of rank-and-file members who
joined Democrats in forcing the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
