<HEADLINE> Swazi Economy Grows by 3.8 Percent Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Swazi economy grew by
3.8 percent last year, the highest since 1990, Southern African
Broadcasting Association reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The high growth rate was a result of recovery of the
agricultural sector, the report quoted Swazi Minister for
Economic Planning Absalom Dlamini as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini said that expansion of large firms also contributed to
the economic achievement.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not specify when the remarks were made.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini said that the population growth rate had also declined
in the country, which he described as another positive aspect to
the economic growth.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the unemployment of the southern African
land-locked country continues to grow at 12 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland has a population of less than one million people,
whose livelihood depends on agriculture and livestock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
