<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin: Intervention only a Temporary Option for Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin suggested on Thursday that the United States would not
intervene to boost the weak yen, but later clarified his remarks
that intervention was an option at a time but in the long it was
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
Testifying to a Senate committee, Rubin said the key to
restoring the yen's fortunes was to promote growth in Japan and
insisted that intervening in currency markets -- central banks
buying yen in the open market in a bid to drive up its value --
would not fundamentally change "anything."
</P>
<P>
"The weakness of the yen reflects the economic conditions in
Japan, and can only be remedied by restoring economic strength
in Japan," Rubin told the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
"Intervention is a temporary tool and not a fundamental
solution," he added.
</P>
<P>
Currency traders interpreted his remarks as all but ruling
out the possibility of joint intervention by major industrial
powers to bolster the yen, prompting a wave of yen selling. The
Japanese currency plunged to 143.65 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
After aides hurriedly slipped him a note following the yen's
slide on the back of his remarks, Rubin clarified his statement,
insisting he did not want to "mislead" markets by implying
intervention was not an option.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want anyone to infer though that we were suggesting
that in all cases intervention was not an appropriate strategy
for short-term effects. We have often said in the past that we
will intervene when appropriate or not intervene when it's not
appropriate. It's always a tool that's available," he told the
committee hearing.
</P>
<P>
"I may have implied that in some sense we have taken
intervention off the table. That certainly would have been a not
correct implication," Rubin later emphasized to reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rubin's bid to rephrase his earlier remarks briefly took some
pressure off the yen, but the battered currency quickly resumed
its slide and traded below 14350 to the dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
