<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, June 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- The Japanese fiscal year for 1997, which ended in
March of this year, contracted from the previous fiscal year for
the first time in 23 years, the Economic Planning Agency (EPA)
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Japan's real gross domestic product (GDP) in the fiscal year
fell an inflation-adjusted 0.7 percent from the previous year,
marking the biggest contraction since the current calculation
method's adoption in 1955, the EPA said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The figure surpassed the previous record fall of 0.5 percent
registered in fiscal 1974 when rapid rises in oil prices hit the
Japanese economy hard, the agency said. (Japan-GDP-Drop)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's House of Representatives, or the lower house
of parliament, rejected Friday a no-confidence motion against
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The motion was voted down at a plenary house session as the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), which dominates the
powerful lower house, was against it.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democratic Party (SDP), LDP's one-time non-cabinet
ally, and New Party Sakigake, another LDP ally, also opposed the
motion, Kyodo News reports said. (Japan-No-Confidence)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA -- The Ethiopian government said Friday that its
policy toward 550,000 Eritreans now residing in Ethiopia "remains
intact" and the Eritreans "can continue to live and work
peacefully in Ethiopia."
</P>
<P>
However, the office of the Ethiopian government spokesperson
said in a news release, "Some who are in leadership positions in
security sensitive posts - such as telecommunications and the
electricity company - must take one month's enforced leave." But
"they can stay in the country," it added.
</P>
<P>
The leadership of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front, which
has a party office in Addis Ababa, must leave the country but
their families have a choice to stay if they wish to, said the
news release. (Ethiopia-Policy Toward Eritreans)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- India proposed Friday to host foreign
secretary-level talks with Pakistan in New Delhi on June 22,
quickly responding to Islamabad's formal offer to resume
bilateral dialogue. (India-Pakistan-Talks) 
</P>
