<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Launches New Roadside Air Pollution Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Environmental Protection
Department (EPD) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) said here Friday that, from Monday on, a new roadside air
pollution index (API) would be released daily in addition to the
existing general API.
</P>
<P>
When announcing this, Assistant Director of Environmental
Protection (Air) Tse Chin-wan said the aim of releasing roadside
API is to arouse more public awareness on air pollution caused by
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The current API follows the practices in many other cities and
reports the quality of the air which people usually breathe in
their homes and offices. Considering that there are many busy
roads in Hong Kong's urban area and that motor vehicles are the
major sources of the air pollution, the EPD has decided to extend
the current API to report also the level of air pollution by the
side of those busy roads, Tse said.
</P>
<P>
The EPD has been operating a monitoring station to measure the
air pollution in Mongkok for many years and the measurement data
have been published on a monthly basis.
</P>
<P>
A new monitoring station has been built in Causeway Bay and
another is being built in Central, both on the Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
The stations are to measure air pollution very close to the
tail-pipes of motor vehicles and the new information collected
through the stations would be of most use to those people who have
to spend long periods of time at roadside locations.
</P>
<P>
Tail-pipe emissions from motor vehicles not only pollute the
air but also often cause direct harm to passing pedestrians. The
control of air pollution from motor vehicles is thus one of the
top priorities of the SAR government, said Tse.
</P>
<P>
Together with the new roadside API, the EPD will now also be
reporting the general API for each of the monitoring stations as
well as using a new set of descriptors to describe different
levels of air pollution, he added.
</P>
<P>
API is a simple way of describing air pollution levels to
provide timely information about air pollution to the public and
to enhance awareness. Since June 1995, the EPD has been reporting
the daily API and making a forecast for the following day.
</P>
<P>
The API forecast serves also as an alert to the public before
the onset of serious air pollution episodes. It helps the general
public, especially susceptible groups such as those with heart or
respiratory illness, to consider taking precautionary measures
when necessary.
</P>
<P>
The EPD reports both general and roadside APIs plus a forecast
for the following day. These indices are calculated by comparing
the measured concentrations of the major air pollutants including
nitrogen dioxide, sulfur dioxide, ozone, carbon monoxide and
respirable suspended particulates, with their respective
health-related Air Quality Objectives (AQOs) established under the
Air Pollution Control Ordinance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0094 </DOCNO>
