<HEADLINE> Tornadoes Hit Indiana Counties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Three tornadoes struck central
Indiana Thursday night, blowing trucks off highways and causing
widespread damage to buildings, the Associated Press reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Only minor injuries were reported to 18 people in five counties
hit by the twisters, the state Emergency Management Agency said.
</P>
<P>
A tornado that touched down on Indianapolis's southeast side
around 6:00 p.m. rolled northwest and stayed on the ground for up
to 110 kilometers, National Weather Service meteorologist Steve
Eddy said.
</P>
<P>
In eastern Marion County and adjoining Hancock County in
Indianapolis area, two tractor-trailers and a United Parcel
Service truck were overturned along a highway.
</P>
<P>
In Greentown, about 65 kilometers north of Indianapolis, eight
people who sought shelter in a basement ended up trapped in a
collapsed home.
</P>
<P>
Tornadoes also were spotted in three counties of southeastern
Nebraska, but the state escaped serious damage. 
