<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Normal Summer Day in Tiananmen Square (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A group of foreign tourists
standing near the Tiananmen Square flagpole the morning with hands
raised in the air were not participating in a rally, but were
instead responding to a roll call conducted by their guide.
</P>
<P>
The initially nervous tour guide from the Dynasty Travel Agency
was noticeably relaxed after verifying the presence of all members
of the group visiting the world's largest square.
</P>
<P>
However, another young guide from the Beijing-based Jinhui
Travel Agency was not as lucky and was anxiously looking for a
missing tourist. "It's extremely difficult to find one person in a
massive square filled with people," said the guide.
</P>
<P>
Beijing continues to enjoy pleasant early summer weather and
crowds of domestic and foreign tourists visiting the square busily
snapped photos of the Monument to the People's Heroes, the Great
Hall of the People and the resplendent Tiananmen Rostrum with its
huge portrait of Chairman Mao Zedong.
</P>
<P>
Tim Olsson, a 32-year-old tourist from Sweden, referred to a
guidebook as he cycled around the square on his new bicycle
purchased at local store. "The first thing I did after arriving in
Beijing was to visit the giant square. It's really beautiful and
fascinating," said Olsson.
</P>
<P>
Li Jianguo and his family from northern Shanxi Province found
accommodations in a small hotel near the square. Li and his wife
cited their desire to watch a national flag-raising ceremony held
in the square at sunrise.
</P>
<P>
While his wife grumbled about the high costs in the Chinese
capital, Li insisted on bringing their little girl to Tiananmen
Square which he regards as the symbol of the nation.
</P>
<P>
Yang Wei, an official from a grain supply department in Nanyang
city in central Henan Province, strolled around the square with
video camera in hand. "I visit the square every time I come to
Beijing. Tiananmen and the square symbolize the dignity of the
nation," said Yang.
</P>
<P>
Mao Zedong stood on the Tiananmen Rostrum on October 1, 1949,
to announce the founding of the People's Republic of China. The
rostrum faces the gigantic square which covers 440,000 square
meters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Normal Summer Day in Tiananmen Square (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese government organizes major activities in the square
to mark special occassions. Most days, however, the square
resembles a giant entertainment venue with local residents flying
kites, children scurry to and fro and young men donning
fashionable sportswear taking advantage of the open area for
rollerblading.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of people also enjoy visiting the cool square on
summer evenings.
</P>
<P>
The plaza at the east entrance to the Great Hall of People
located on the west side of the square is placid when compared to
the hustle and bustle associated with Tiananmen. People are
prohibited from strolling along the plaza which is one of the most
important diplomatic venues for the government. Chinese leaders
have rolled out the red carpet in the plaza to greet several
hundred foreign leaders over the past two decades. Related
ceremonies held in the Great Hall of the People during bad weather.
</P>
<P>
"I know that welcoming ceremonies are scheduled when the
national flags of China and various countries are displayed on
Chang'an Avenue which separates the Tiananmen Rostrum and
Tiananmen Square," said Liu Caizhen, a cleaner who works in the
square.
</P>
<P>
"Ceremonies were held a few days ago to welcome the Italian
president, and I understand that President Jiang Zemin will
welcome U.S. President Bill Clinton in the plaza," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
"My friends say some U.S. senators are opposed President
Clinton's participation in welcome ceremonies scheduled for
Tiananmen Square. It seems they lack any sense of protocol and
propriety," said Yang Yueru, a young teacher from the China
Agricultural University.
</P>
<P>
Yang referred Tiananmen Square to China's big parlor, and said
that how can a host receive a guest not in the parlor.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. side warmly welcomed President Jiang (last fall) and
hospitable Chinese will in return leave a deep impression on
President Clinton during his China visit," said Yang, a 1989
graduate from the English Department at Central China Teachers
University.
</P>
<P>
Visitors and nearby residents gradually left the square later
in the evening. Many returned home to watch the live telecast of
the soccer World Cup under way in France.
</P>
<P>
The night wore on and the giant "M" designating the fast-food
McDonalds franchise store sparkled in the sky to the south of the
square. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
