<HEADLINE> World Bank to Provide New Financial Assistance to Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) agreed in
principle to provide a 199 million U.S. dollar loan for a power
distribution and a disaster recovery project in Vietnam in 1998,
Vietnam News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
More financial assistance will be provided by the bank this
year to help Vietnam with five other projects -- safe blood for
medical purposes, economic structural adjustment, urban
transportation, higher education and agricultural diversification.
</P>
<P>
WB Chief Representative in Vietnam, Andrew Steer, said the bank
planned to provide a loan of 2 billion dollars to the country
during 1998 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The bank has pledged a total of 1.62 billion dollars for 16
economic, social and infrastructure projects over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
WB also granted Vietnam non-refundable technical assistance to
accelerate the implementation of WB-funded projects, including
consultancy services on macro-economic management, business
reform, strategies and policies to develop industry,
communications, the financial sector and accounting
systems. 
</P>
