<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 39 Parties to Participate in Cambodian Assembly Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A total of 39 political parties
will field candidates in the forthcoming elections in Cambodia,
the National Election Committee (NEC) announced Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The parties, which were registered on May 7, were formally
approved, including Prince Ranariddh's Funcinpec party, after an
examination that lasted one month, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
After the second discussion on the reintegration of troops
loyal to Prince Ranariddh failed on Wednesday, some analysts
suspected that Funcinpec would not be allowed to take part in the
elections.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Prince Ranariddh warned in Phnom Penh that the
international community would withdraw its support from the
elections and would not recognize the results if he and his party
could not run.
</P>
<P>
He said he would ask "the friends of Cambodia" to help mediate
the reintegration of resistance forces, as well as pardons for his
top military commanders before the election.
</P>
<P>
All the 122 seats in the National Assembly will be contested
in the July 26 elections.
</P>
<P>
In the 1993 elections, which was monitored by
U.N. representatives, Funcinpec won 58 seats out of the 120 seats,
while Hun Sen's opposition Cambodian People's Party gained 52
seats.
</P>
<P>
Only 20 parties took part in the last elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
