<HEADLINE> Reunification Gifts Find Permanent Display Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Special arrangements are being
made to permanently display the enormous gifts presented by the
Chinese mainland to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) on its establishment last year.
</P>
<P>
The gifts, presented by 31 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities, will be shown at major public facilities, such as
the spacious new airport and the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center (HKCEC), as well as government office buildings
and museums, a government spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The HKCEC and the VIP lounge of the new airport will each
eventually have seven and four gifts for permanent display and the
large concentrations of the gifts should help create a positive
visual impact for visitors to Hong Kong, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Another major recipient is the Hong Kong Heritage Museum in Sha
Tin, the "New Territories," which will have six pieces on
permanent display when it is completed in 2000.
</P>
<P>
All of the gifts are "gems of superb craftsmanship,
representing the best of contemporary Chinese art," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Security, public exposure and the proposed venues' size and
floor loading are among factors considered when allocating the
gifts of embroidery, ceramics, lacquer work, tapestry and stone
sculpture.
</P>
<P>
Some of the items will be on display here for a month to
commemorate the first anniversary of the reunification of Hong
Kong with China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
