<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Rejects Indian Talks Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Friday termed the
Indian offer for resumption of talks on June 22 as a "traditional
gimmickry of Indian diplomacy" and reiterated its call for active
international engagement in the dialogue process between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Thursday made an offer for the resumption of talks to
India on the basis agreed upon by both countries on June 23 last
year, a Foreign Office spokesman said in a statement Friday
evening, responding to the Indian Foreign Ministry's offer earlier
in the day to resume bilateral talks on June 22.
</P>
<P>
"Instead of responding positively to this offer of talks on the
agreed basis India has asked for the resumption of talks on the
basis of the proposals made by New Delhi in January 1998," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"These proposals were not acceptable to Pakistan as a working
basis for resumption of talks as these were totally unrealistic
and reflected India's consistently negative and non-serious
approach toward dialogue," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indians have also rejected Pakistan's offer of a
formal test ban treaty between the two countries to defuse nuclear
tensions in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Even this rejection does not surprise Pakistan. India is
averse to any constructive proposal which it deems may serve as a
check on her provocative and hegemonistic policies," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This yet again highlights that bilaterally the dialogue will
remain deadlocked or non-productive."
</P>
<P>
"It forcefully underscores the imperative of the engagement of
the international community with this process in some form, namely
good offices, mediation or initiatives by the U.N. secretary
general," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Pakistan formally conveyed its proposal for
resumption of talks to the Indian high commissioner here, saying
the Pakistani government invites India to send its foreign
secretary to Islamabad for talks on June 20. Meanwhile, Pakistan
declared a unilateral moratorium on nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, an Indian Foreign Ministry announced in New
Delhi that the country would host foreign secretary-level talks
with Pakistan on June 22.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretaries of Pakistan and India agreed in their
talks here on June 23, 1997, to discuss eight issues including
Jammu and Kashmir and peace and security in their future parleys.
This was the first time that the two countries had agreed to put
Kashmir on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
"By ignoring the agreed basis for talks and calling for
resumption of dialogue on the basis of its own proposals India has
in effect once again sabotaged the dialogue process," the
Pakistani spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
It may be recalled that the five permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council in their meeting in Geneva last week as well as
the U.N. Security Council have urged resumption of dialogue for
addressing the root-cause of tension in South Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. secretary general is also actively engaged in
promoting the dialogue process, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"All these efforts are now being negated by India with her
obstructionist policies in defiance of the will of the
international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has welcomed the proposed visit of the U.N. secretary
general's special envoy to the region. However, India has rejected
any third-party engagement in the two countries' dialogue process.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
