<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Container Throughput on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Kwai Chung Container
Port handled 3.79 million twenty-foot equivalent units (TEUs) of
containers in the first five months of 1998, up 4 percent from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
But the container throughput edged up just 1 percent in May,
Richard Yuen, secretary to the Hong Kong Port and Maritime Board,
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Combining container terminals at Kwai Chung and mid-stream and
river trade together, the container throughput was 2 million TEUs
for January and February this year, an increase of 4 percent over
the same period last year, Yuen said. Figures for March to May are
not yet available.
</P>
<P>
"Although the Southeast Asian financial turmoil is expected to
have some impact on the Hong Kong port this year, we still expect
a positive, healthy growth for our port this year," Yuen said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong maintained its position as the world's busiest
container port for the sixth year in a row in 1997. Including
container terminals and mid-stream and river trade, it handled 4.5
million containers in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
