<HEADLINE> HK Railway Projects Bring New Jobs: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Future railway infrastructure
development will bring more job opportunities in the next few
years, Hong Kong Secretary for Transport Nicholas Ng said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 64-billion-HK-dollar (8.2 billion U.S. dollars) West Rail
(Phase 1) project would create about 7,000 jobs in the employment
market in the coming 18 months, he told a ceremony to mark the
completion of the Kowloon-Canton Railway Hung Hom Station
renovation and expansion project.
</P>
<P>
"Taking into account the Mass Transit Railway (MTR) Tseung Kwan
O extension and other railway development projects including
consultancy, the number of jobs will exceed 10,000 when all these
projects enter their peak construction phase," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Government figures showed that unemployment hit a relatively
high level of 3.9 percent between February and April due to
stagnant economic activities.
</P>
<P>
Ng pointed out that the government has taken an active approach
toward railway development to meet the demand of the traveling
public.
</P>
<P>
About 110 billion HK dollars (14.1 billion U.S. dollars) will
be spent on the three priority railway projects -- West Rail
(Phase 1), MTR Tseung Kwan O Extension and Ma On Shan to Tai Wai
Rail Link. They will all be completed within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The official added that the government is now examining other
new rail links to cope with the long-term land and housing
development in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
