<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Increases Allocation for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has increased
allocation by 6 percent or 889. 3 million rupees (about 20 million
U.S. dollars) for the education and training sector in the
forthcoming 1998-1999 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget for 1998-1999 (July 1-June 30) unveiled
here Friday afternoon by Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz, an amount
of 207 million rupees (about 4.7 million dollars) out of the total
provision has been allocated for expansion and development of
university education.
</P>
<P>
During the year, about 40 Pakistani scholars will be sent
abroad for higher studies. About 600 foreign students are also
expected to seek admission in various institutions of the country
on a self-finance basis.
</P>
<P>
Under the Public Sector Development Program, 140 million rupees
(about 3.2 million dollars) has been allocated for the
establishment of Non-Formal Basic Educational schools.
</P>
<P>
The official literacy rate of Pakistan, whose population stands
at about 130 million, is just 37 percent, one of the lowest in the
world.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech to the nation on Thursday evening, Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif vowed to promote literacy and promised that
in the next five years all children in the country will get
education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
