<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Opens Court Trials to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing No.1 Intermediate
People's Court will become the nation's first intermediate court
to enhance external supervision by opening trials to the public.
</P>
<P>
A Wednesday announcement stipulated that Chinese citizens over
the age of 18 will be allowed to attend court hearings by
presenting appropriate identifications, with journalists permitted
to report on any open trial.
</P>
<P>
"Open trials will enhance the fairness of court proceedings,"
said Ma Aidi, president of the Beijing No.1 Intermediate
People's Court.
</P>
<P>
The practice will also help increase the transparency of
trials, self-discipline the judiciary, and protect the legitimate
rights of individuals facing trial, said Ma.
</P>
<P>
Chinese laws stipulate that all cases with the exception of
those involving national secrets, personal privacy and minors
should be tried openly. And, verdicts for cases not tried openly
must be announced to the general public.
</P>
<P>
However, few people were allowed to attend hearings in the
past, because of a small number of courts, insufficient functions
in the design of the court, a large number of cases, and the
length of trials.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing court invested over 200,000 yuan ( 24,000 US
dollars) to install an electronic screen and security gate in
order to guarantee the safety of the court and ensure convenient
access to those attending hearings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
