<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Friday:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton issued a broad defense of his
decision to seek closer relations with Beijing, arguing that
expanding cooperation is critical to preserving U.S. security and
"building a stable international order."
</P>
<P>
-- Pakistan announced a moratorium on further nuclear weapons
tests, joining arch-rival India in calling a halt to underground
detonations that have prompted international condemnation of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton, responding to Congressional criticism of
his forthcoming summit meeting in China, described his policy of
cooperation with Beijing as "principled and pragmatic."
</P>
<P>
-- NATO defense ministers ordered contingency plans for bombing
Serbian military targets in Kosovo and even in Serbia. They say
they would also stage a huge demonstration of force just across
the border to force Yugoslavia to stop attack in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The yen continued its fall against dollar on Thursday and
investors braced for the release of figures expected to show
that Japan's economy contracted for a second-straight quarter.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian markets are dropping again after a respite last
week, as uncertainty persists over whether the West will extend
stabilization funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
