<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Introduces Strict Limits On Auto Emissions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Government
announced strict limits on automotive emissions today.
</P>
<P>
However, officials pointed out that the full effectiveness of
the new standards will require strict regulations on automotive
service stations and repair shops.
</P>
<P>
A bulletin released by the State Bureau of Machinery Industry
(SBMI) stipulates that all automobiles rolling off the nation's
production lines after July 1 this year will be required to reach
the new emission control standards equivalent to requirements in
European nations during the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
All automobiles weighing less than 3.5 tons will be subject to
a reduction of between 43 percent and 66 percent in emissions of
CO, HC and NOx.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin also contains emission standards for petroleum
and diesel engines produced domestically. Plans for 2002 call for
raising the standards to the levels in European nations during the
1990s, and still further to the global level by 2010.
</P>
<P>
SEMI Deputy Director Zhang Xiaoyu told a press conference today
that emission control standards will be complemented by
standardizing maintenance services.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China lacks a national regulatory system
for automotive maintenance and repair services. Zhang said the
common problem of related services is their failure to meet
technical standards set by automobile manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Experts from relevant government institutes claim that proper
servicing will ensure that Chinese-made automobiles maintain
emission standards for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
They also note that joint experiments conducted by Chinese
government departments and US-based Ford Motor Company prove the
point.
</P>
<P>
However, the experts note that many automobiles fail to meet
emission standards due to improper servicing.
</P>
<P>
China plans to invest some 2.6 billion yuan (313 million US
dollars) to develop its ability to produce electronically
controlled fuel injection engines. In addition, the use of
unleaded gasoline is spreading throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
A joint Sino-US research and development project on emission
gas converters has entered the road testing phase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
