<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Exhibits Mature Securities Market Management  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China's maturation into an able
regulator of its securities market is best indicated by the
market's smooth operation and steady growth during a period in
which neighboring markets have been shaken by financial
instability.
</P>
<P>
The economists and stock analysts in China share the view and
note that the country's growing capability can be seen in the
improved management of the securities management system, as well
as proper policy orientation and maturing expertise in regulating
supply and demand on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
China initiated the reform of its securities management system
earlier this year by designating the China Securities Management
Commission (CSRC) as the sole administrator of the securities
market. Economists note the move will greatly enhance the
management efficiency of the market.
</P>
<P>
The government also adopted a series of measures designed to to
create a steadily developing securities market which will
facilitate the nation's state-owned enterprise reform effort.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's reduction of bank interest rates at the end
of March helped invigorate the bearish and sluggish stock
market. The move was accompanied by improved market sentiment
which led to rising stock prices and a daily turnover of more than
13 billion yuan (1.57 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Regulations governing the securities investment fund also went
into effect in March and reflected the strong determination to
foster rational and institutional investors in order to stablize
the stock market. Three securities investment funds are in place
and a fourth is expected to be offered to the public next
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Americans to Visit China This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China anticipates an 8-10 percent
rise in the number of U.S. tourists visiting the country during
1998, up from the 616,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Officials from China National Tourism Administration (CNTA)
announced the projected growth at the ongoing Sino-U.S. tourism
exchange fair.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economy has witnessed steady growth in recent years,
with Sino-U.S. relations entering a new stage of development and
air traffic between the two countries on the rise. The officials
noted that visa procedures for U.S. tourists to China have
been simplified.
</P>
<P>
The fair attracted dozens of officials and scholars from the
CNTA, China Tourism Association, Beijing Municipal Public Security
Bureau, Air China, University of California, U.S. Champion
Holidays, and Palm Springs Tourism Corporation.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to
China, participants discussed expanded tourism cooperation between
the two countries, with special emphasis on how China expands
U.S. tourism market.
</P>
<P>
U.S. participants said that an increasing number of Americans
have exhibited a desire to visit China. They also noted the
increased diversification of the country's tourism market and the
increased standardization of reception work.
</P>
<P>
Air China recently opened its Beijing-Los Angeles route and
plans to add three flights to the U.S later this year.
</P>
<P>
The fair was jointly sponsored by U.S. Champion Holidays
and China Xinhai International Travel Service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
