<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Exhibits Mature Securities Market Management (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unruly market players have been subject to harsh penalties as
part of the effort to introduce special measures to squeeze out
market bubbles. Companies suspected to filing false annual reports
are not only subject to "special treatment" which sets official
limits on price fluctuations, but also face extremely strict
examination of interim reports. Trading is immediately suspended
with the emergence of abnormal price movements.
</P>
<P>
"The measures will prompt listed companies to improve their
performance, curb excessive speculation and effectively protect
the interests of investors," according to one market analyst.
</P>
<P>
Yet another example of the efficient market managements
involves the growing ability to expand the market without creating
volatile fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the 30 companies and three funds listed on
the A-share market during the first four months of the year had
total capital of 20.48 billion yuan (2.47 billion US dollars), up
4.89 billion yuan (589 million US dollars) on last year's same
period.
</P>
<P>
The good timing of stock listings ensured that the market
remained steady in spite of the rapid expansion. By the end of
April, Stock indices on the Shanghai and Shenzhen markets grew
52.4 percent and 62 percent respectively when compared to the
previous year's period, with limited fluctuations standing at 21
percent and 11.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
