<HEADLINE> Pakistan Unveils 1998-1999 Fiscal Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Friday unveiled its
1998-1999 budget with an 8.4-precent increase in the defense
spending, a 50-percent cut in non-development expenditure and a
broadening of the tax basis.
</P>
<P>
The new fiscal year (July 1-June 30) budget, which was approved
by a cabinet meeting chaired by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif Friday
morning, is to be presented by Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz to the
National Assembly late in the afternoon. The budget proposals are
likely to be adopted by June 30.
</P>
<P>
This will be the second national budget by the Sharif
government since it came to power in February last year.
</P>
<P>
And the budget is being announced at a time when the country is
facing economic sanctions by the West for its nuclear tests in
response to those of India last month.
</P>
<P>
According to the new budget, the total outlay is 606.3 billion
rupees (about 13.8 billion U.S. dollars), 9.8 percent higher than
the budget estimates and 11.1 percent over the revised estimates
of 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
The defense expenditure is estimated at 145 billion rupees
(about 3.25 billion dollars), indicating increases of 8.2 and 8.4
percent over budget and revised estimates of 1997-1998
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The resource availability during 1998-1999 is estimated at
550.7 billion rupees (about 12.5 billion dollars), 10.8 and 6.1
percent more than the budget and revised estimates of 1997-1998
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Net revenue receipts for 1998-1999 are estimated at 367.1
billion rupees (about 8.3 billion dollars) which indicates
increases of 9.3 and 11 percent over the budget and revised
estimates of 1997-1998 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The receipts from external resources in 1998-1999 are estimated
at 142 billion rupees (about 3.2 billion dollars), 9.7 and 14.7
percent higher than the budget and revised estimates of 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
The overall expenditure during the 1998-1999 is estimated at
606.3 billion rupees (about 13.8 billion dollars), of which
current expenditure is 495.7 billion rupees (about 11.3 billion
dollars) and development expenditure 110.6 billion rupees (about
2.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The share of current expenditure in total budgetary outlay for
1998-1999 is 81.8 percent as compared to 83.7 percent in budget
and revised estimates for 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure on the running of civil government is estimated
at 43.5 billion rupees (about 987 million dollars), a decrease of
6.3 percent over budget estimates and 5.2 percent over revised
estimates of 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
The provinces will get 135 billion rupees (about 3.06 billion
dollars) during 1998-1999, which is 8.7 and 14 percent higher than
the budget estimates and revised estimates of 1997-1998
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The size of public sector development program for 1998-1999 is
110.6 billion rupees (abut 2.5 billion dollars), a rise of 22.8
percent over the budget estimates and 24.1 percent over the
revised estimates of 1997-1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
