<HEADLINE> India proposes Talks With Pakistan in New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- India made a quick response
Friday to Pakistan's offer for a resumption of high-level talks
between the two neighbors by proposing to host foreign
secretary-level talks in New Delhi on June 22.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the External Affairs Ministry said this
afternoon that India would be happy to resume the round of foreign
secretary talks which was adjourned in New Delhi last September.
</P>
<P>
"For this purpose we invite an official delegation led by the
foreign secretary of Pakistan to visit New Delhi on June 22," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's offer for resuming talks was officially conveyed
Thursday to Indian High Commissioner in Islamabad Satish Chandra.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman did not make a direct response to Pakistan's
offer for a no-nuclear test agreement with India, saying this and
other suggestions could be discussed under the first agenda item
of the proposed foreign secretary-level talks which was peace and
security and confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
Other subjects for discussions put forward by India include
Jammu and Kashmir, terrorism and drug trafficking, economic and
commercial cooperation and promotion of friendly exchanges in
various fields.
</P>
<P>
He said India "is committed to fostering a relationship of
trust and friendship with Pakistan, based on mutual respect and
regard for each other's concerns." 
