<HEADLINE> Shell-funded Lubrication Oil Co. Starts Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Zhejiang Shell Oil and
Petrochemical Co. Ltd, a Shell-funded joint venture, started
business in east China's Zhejiang Province today.
</P>
<P>
Brain Anderson, chief director of Shell Companies in Northeast
Asia, said: "I'm glad that the Zhejiang Shell lubrication
oil plant has been completed and put into production. It will
directly supply quality lubrication oil to the Chinese market."
</P>
<P>
The Shell group has 85 percent of the shares in the 29.8
million-U.S.-dollar plant, with the rest held by Jiaxing Zhapu
Port Co. and Transportation Materials Co. of Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
Seated in Zhapu Port near Shanghai, the new plant will produce
45,000 tons of lubrication oil for automobiles and industrial use.
</P>
<P>
Zhapu is also home to another Shell-funded company, Zhejiang
Shell Bitumen Co. Ltd, which became operational last year at a
cost of 20.9 million U.S. dollars with an annual capacity of
250,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
One of the earliest foreign companies that enter China, Shell
has so far had a contractual investment of one billion
U.S. dollars in the country. The figure is expected to reach three
billion dollars at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Shell, one of the world's oil giant, has expanded its business
in China from oil and natural gas exploration to oil
product processing and selling.  
</P>
