<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Economy Posts Negative Growth in Fiscal 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese fiscal year for 1997, which
ended in March of this year, contracted from the previous fiscal year
for the first time in 23 years, the Economic Planning Agency (EPA)
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Japan's real gross domestic product (GDP) in the fiscal year fell
an inflation-adjusted 0.7 percent from the previous year, marking the
biggest contraction since the current calculation method's adoption in
1955, the EPA said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The figure surpassed the previous record fall of 0.5 percent
registered in fiscal 1974 when rapid rises in oil prices hit the
Japanese economy hard, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The EPA attributed the contraction to negative impact on the
Japanese economy by the financial crisis in Asia and the collapse
of major financial institutions in Japan last fall.
</P>
<P>
Japan set a target GDP growth rate of 1.9 percent at the
beginning of fiscal 1997, then lowered it to 0.1 percent last
December.
</P>
<P>
GDP measures the value of goods and services produced within
the nation. Real GDP figures are adjusted for inflation and
seasonal variations.
</P>
<P>
GDP in the January-March quarter dropped 1.3 percent from the
previous quarter in real terms, or an annualized fall of 5.3
percent, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Domestic demand reduced the country's GDP growth by a negative
1.0 percentage point, and external demand pushed it down by 0.4
percentage points, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Among GDP components, personal consumption, which accounts for
some 60 percent of the GDP aggregate, edged up 0.1 percent in the
reporting quarter, after marking a revised 1.0 percent decline in
the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
Housing investment also rose by 1.7 percent from the previous
quarter, posting the first growth in five quarters.
</P>
<P>
However, corporate capital spending, another engine for the
economy, decreased by 5.1 percent in the reporting quarter, the
worst decline since the April-June period in 1965 when it marked a
6.1 percent fall, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Exports fell 3.8 percent from the previous quarter, the first
decrease since the January-March quarter in 1986, when they fell
by 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japan's real gross national product (GNP) -- GDP
plus net income from abroad -- declined by 1.5 percent, or at an
annualized rate of 5.8 percent, in the reporting quarter.
</P>
<P>
Real GNP for the full fiscal year shrank by 0.6 percent from
the previous year, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the overall GDP data, economists at private
financial institutions said that it would be difficult for the
government to achieve its 1.9 percent growth target for fiscal
1998 under the current economic situation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Plumber to Be Awarded Medal for Act of Bravery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Plumber Lee Ying-kwong, who
sacrificed his life to save children Tuesday, will be awarded by
the Hong Kong government the Medal for Bravery (Gold), the highest
award for bravery, the government said Friday.
</P>
<P>
On the recommendation of the Honors Committee, Chief Executive
Tung Chee Hwa has decided to award the honor to the hero, whose
act has been widely acclaimed by local media and the wider public.
</P>
<P>
Two boys, aged 12 and 9, fell into a flooded nullah Tuesday
when torrential rain lashed Hong Kong. Lee, 51, who was at the
vicinity at the time, went down into the nullah to save the two
boys.
</P>
<P>
After saving one of the boys and carrying him to safety, Lee
went back the second time to save the other. He was swept away by
the raging flood while trying to reach the second boy and was
drowned.
</P>
<P>
Lee showed the most conspicuous courage in circumstances of
extreme danger and the medal will be a recognition of his bravery
and selfless sacrifice, said the government.
</P>
<P>
Lee's award will be published together with the other awards in
 the 1998 Honors List in July. The presentation ceremony will be
held later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
