<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Farmers Imprisoned for Killing Tiger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Wang Limin and Zou Changzhong,
two farmers in northeast China's Jilin Province, have been
sentenced to four years' and three years and a half imprisonment
respectively for illegal killing of a Siberian tiger in Changbai
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
Zou Zhitang, also a farmer, who was not involved in the tiger
killing but sold the tiger bones, had two years' probation under
suspended sentence of two years imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
They were also fined between 1,500 yuan (180 U.S. dollars) and
2,000 yuan (240 dollars) for breaking the Law on the Protection of
Wildlife, according to a local court in Hunchun forest region.
</P>
<P>
Four farmers, two of them are still at large, killed a
100-kilogram male tiger held by an iron device in Changbai
Mountians in October, 1993 with hunting guns and hid the tiger
skin and bones in the houses of Wang Limin and Zou Changzhong.
</P>
<P>
Zou Zhitang took away the tiger bones hidden in a big vat in
Zou Changzhong's house and sold them at 14,500 yuan (1,747
dollars) in Hunchun City in the Changbai Mountains area.
</P>
<P>
Zou Zhitang was seized by local police soon after police
received a report. Later, Wang Limin and Zou Changzhong were also
detained.
</P>
<P>
Zou Zhitang had handed over all the money obtained from selling
the tiger bones before the court ruling.
</P>
<P>
A UN-funded investigation in spring this year shows that three
to five Siberian tigers are residing in Hunchun forest
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
