<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Construction Industry Can Face Challenges of Change: Housing Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The construction industry of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) is in a best ever
position to face tough challenges of change, Tony Miller, vice
chairman of the Housing Authority and director of housing, said
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There can be few moments in our history when the challenges
have been greater. However, there can be few moments in our
history when we have had a construction industry better able to
face the challenges of change," Miller said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar of the on-going International Building
and Construction Exposition (IBEX'98) here on Friday, Miller said
that at a time when other parts of the economy may be running
slack, the industry is set to continue to run at full capacity for
several years to come.
</P>
<P>
Miller defended the government's decision to construct 50,000
units of publicly built houses every year, saying that although
half of SAR's population live in public housing, 148,000 families
are still waiting for public rental housing and it takes an
average of 6.5 years to get in. A steady production of that amount
of units will enable the Housing Authority to bring the average
waiting time down to three years.
</P>
<P>
The authorities will have 200,000 flats under construction at
any one time for the next three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the issue of employment, Miller said that the estimate
of new jobs by SAR's public works and infrastructure projects over
the next 12 months is nearly 60,000 not including housing.
</P>
<P>
The public housing program had in recent years employed around
12,000 skilled and semi-skilled workers full-time. With still more
intense activity expected for the period of three years to come,
some 3,000 such jobs on site are to be added, he said.
</P>
<P>
Miller admitted that the local industry faces the real
challenges of quality, safety, environmentally friendly practices
and efficiency. Concerning the issue of quality, everyone
involved must start with a sincere commitment coupled with
professionalism, accountability and a clear understanding of
expectations, he said.
</P>
<P>
As for safety, the SAR government is determined to develop a
safety management systems. By 1999, all construction sites in the
SAR will be covered by a system which includes a contract
requirement for safety and independent safety auditing, he said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day IBEX'98 provides a marketing platform for more
than 200 companies from over 10 countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
