<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Have First Self-Regulatory Taxi Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's taxi industry
plans to set up its first self-regulatory organization,
sources of the industry said.
</P>
<P>
The new body, provisionally named the Interim National Taxi
Council (INTC), will represent all national taxi associations and
established provincial bodies, local daily Business Day Friday
quoted the sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Transport Minister Mac Maharja confirmed that regulation of
the industry will be among the council's tasks.
</P>
<P>
According to an industry source, the first business of the
interim body will be to prepare for a permanent council based on
proportional representation.
</P>
<P>
Within two years, each taxi owner will vote for an
association to represent him or her on the council. In the
interim, representation will be based on the composition of
provincial and metropolitan structures.
</P>
<P>
It was believed the establishment of the INTC will be
instrumental to curb violent activities and disorder in South
African taxi industry.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people were reportedly killed and wounded in
clashes among taxi owners, who were in fierce business
competition, in the past few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
