<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Stays at 144 Yen Level in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Weighted down by profit-taking after
hitting highs during the day last seen in August 1990, the
U.S. dollar hovered at 144 yen line Friday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 144.01-04 yen at 5 p.m. local
time, down from 144.53-56 yen at 9 a.m., and 144.05-15 yen late
Thursday in New York.
</P>
<P>
Japanese exporters and U.S. fund operators kept the dollar's
lofty levels against the yen intact, selling the U.S. currency on
rises to book profits, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
They said the underlying yen-selling trend has not faded, now
that the Japanese government has released worse-than-expected
gross domestic product (GDP) data.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Planning Agency (EPA) said Friday Japan's GDP for
the fiscal year ended March 1998 dropped, for the first time in 23
years, by an inflation adjusted 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Japan's GDP for January-March fell by 1.3 percent,
or an annualized rate of 5.3 percent -- more than the worst fall
of 4.0 percent predicted by economists, and significantly worse
than the economists' average 1.1 percent drop forecast.
</P>
<P>
The market is trying to test 145 yen, said an analyst, adding
that if the dollar breaks 145, the next target will be 147 yen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects to Have Securities Law: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China expects to pass a
legislation governing securities trading this year, today's
"Shanghai Securities News" disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Li Yining, vice chairman of the Financial and Economic
Committee of National People's Congress, China's supreme
legislative organ, believes that the law will standardize the
development of China's fledgling securities market, according to
the paper.
</P>
<P>
Li, a well-known economist of Beijing University, points out
that China needs to develop its securities market in its reform to
turn the state-owned enterprises into shareholding companies.
</P>
<P>
The securities market is also indispensable in helping with
readjusting industrial structure, optimizing resources, and
restructuring enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The securities market are also replacing the banks to become a
major source of fund raising for high-tech development, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
