<HEADLINE> Japan Provides Grant Assistance to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
agreed to provide a grant assistance of 999.172 million yen (7.3
million U.S. dollars) to Nepal under its debt relief measures,
Nepal's official RSS news agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The amount is in lieu of the repayment of the principal and the
accrued interest of the outstanding loans extended by the Japanese
government to the Nepali government, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Japan provided its first grant to Nepal under the debt relief
measures in fiscal year 1997, and has been providing such grants
twice every year for Nepal to procure commodities which are
essential for its various development works, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Ambassador to Nepal Tomohiko Yanase was quoted as
saying that the grant assistance has been provided with the basic
objective of assisting the Nepali government in procuring
essential commodities like petroleum products, fire fighting
engines, fertilizers, medicines, communication, survey and
construction equipment and other equipment related to
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the biggest donor to Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
