<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official on China's Labor and Social Security Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government plans to
accomplish the early stage of building a labor system and a social
security system in five years, said a Chinese official here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Such a system, said Li Qiyan, vice-minister of China's newly
established Ministry of Labor and Social Security, will secure
more job opportunities and enjoy social security for workers.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing here, Li said his ministry will undertake
the historic mission to facilitate China's current economic
development and a socialist market economy in the making.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister is here for the ongoing annual International
Labor Conference of the International Labor Organization (ILO).
</P>
<P>
China is ready to cooperate with the ILO and its members and
"learn from all other countries' useful experience in tackling the
problems of employment and social security," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the official said, his country will further
improve labor and social security laws, regulations and policies
"in the light of our specific national conditions."
</P>
<P>
"The realization of the above goal will be our country's new
contribution to the development of the ILO and progress of the
human society," he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, Li recalled, China has made
remarkable achievements in economic development and social
progress by implementing the policy of reform and opening-up, thus
improving the living standards of its people, who account for one
fifth of the world's population.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, like many other countries, China, the most
populous developing nation in the world, is faced with great
challenges in the fields of employment and social security.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government pays great attention to absorbing useful
contents of international labor standards in the process of labor
legislation, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the years to come, the Chinese government will, as always,
work hard for the healthy development of activities concerning
labor standards," he said.
</P>
<P>
About the ILO, he called for its members to handle differences
in accordance with the principles of mutual respect, seek common
ground, and work for solutions on the basis of broad consensus.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government is ready to make joint efforts with
other parties to bring a more responsive and cooperative ILO into
the new century," Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
