<HEADLINE> Philippines Celebrates Centennial of Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Filipinos Friday put on a national
fiesta to mark the centennial of the Philippines' declaration of
independence from Spain.
</P>
<P>
The official celebration started with the simultaneous ringing
of church bells across the country in the early morning. At 7
o'clock in the morning, President Fidel Ramos and dignitaries from
32 countries and regions re-enacted the declaration of
independence 100 years ago in Kawit, Cavite province, south of
Manila.
</P>
<P>
On June 12, 1898, Emilio Aguinaldo, leader of the revolutionary
movement, raised the first national flag and proclaimed the
country's independence from Spain which had ruled the country for
333 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President-elect Joseph Estrada hoisted a national
flag at Rizal Park as flag raising ceremonies were held
simultaneously all over the country.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the celebration was a centennial parade at
Luneta Park. The parade depicted the Filipinos' daily life
including fishing and planting and the Filipinos' struggle against
Spanish colonialist and Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
In his early message to the nation, President Ramos said that
"no other event...can ever approximate the full significance of
the stirring moment" of June 12, 1898, in Kawit, Cavite.
</P>
<P>
Friday's celebration, he said, would "showcase our collective
achievements, our future aspirations and our capabilities as
individual achievers and as a competitive national team".
</P>
<P>
The grand parade started at 2:30 p.m. and lasted about five
hours. Immediately after, people would be treated a spectacular
fireworks display unprecedented in the Philippine history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
