<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drugs to Curb Anti-Apartheid Campaign Revealed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Former South African police
officers revealed that apartheid security leaders once
ordered them to make use of drugs such as Mandrax, LSD and Dagga
in the manufacturing of substances for crowd control during
anti-apartheid riots.
</P>
<P>
Lothar Neethling, former South African Police forensic expert
Thursday told the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC)
hearing in Cape Town that Mandrax, Dagga and LSD, confiscated
from dealers, were used in experiments aimed at producing a
powder that could then be sprayed into rioting crowds to sedate
them.
</P>
<P>
The TRC is a special court authorized by the Government of
National Unity led by President Nelson Mandela to investigate
various kinds of criminal and violent activities during the
apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
Also revealed Thursday was that Roodeplaat Research
Laboratories (RRL), where substances to induce infertility in
black women and cultures for deadly diseases such as cholera were
manufactu, was nothing other than a base for the apartheid
security forces' dirty tricks campaign against their political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
A plan was hatched to poison President Nelson Mandela after
his release from prison with a substance which would cause steady
deterioration of brain function, according to Schalk van
Rensburg, head of research at RRL. Mandela was released in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Among the victims of RRL's poisons was former South African
Council of Churches secretary-general Frank Chikane, now
Director-General in Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's office. He
survived only because the attack was botched.
</P>
<P>
In the words of RRL former head Daan Goosen, the apartheid
government spent at least 100 million Rand (nearly 20 million
U.S. Dollars ) of the tax-payers' money to establish RRL. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
