<HEADLINE> U.S. First National Ocean Conference Opens in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- In the 21st century, the world
will look increasingly to the oceans for food, fuel, new medicine
and other resources, said U.S. Vice President Al Gore on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the U.S. first national ocean
conference in Monterey, California, Gore said, "Already we see
troubling signs that marine resources are overstressed."
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the Clinton administration wants to
spend an additional 30 million U.S. dollars over the next three
years to improve the health of oceans.
</P>
<P>
The money, which environmental activists said was inadequate,
will go for new scientific exploration, preservation of coral
reefs in 18 locations and a new network of buoys and satellites to
monitor climate change.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 top scientists, business leaders and policy
makers attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, governor of California Pete Wilson and U.S. Senate
Barbara Boxer have reportedly urged President Clinton to extend an
existing moratorium, which expires in two years, to keep new oil
rigs from dotting the pristine coast.
</P>
<P>
Banning oil drilling off the California coast has long been a
top priority of environmentalists, who are concerned about
aesthetics as well as the danger posed to the marine ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
Gore said Clinton would have more to say on the subject when he
arrives in Monterey on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No-Confidence Motion Against Japanese PM Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives, or
the lower house of parliament, rejected Friday a no-confidence
motion against Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The motion was voted down at a plenary house session as the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), which dominates the
powerful lower house, was against it.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democratic Party (SDP), LDP's one-time non-cabinet
ally, and New Party Sakigake, another LDP ally, also opposed the
motion, Kyodo News reports said.
</P>
<P>
The second of the kind against the Hashimoto cabinet, the
motion was filed Thursday by the Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ),
the Liberal Party (LP) and the Japanese Communist Party (JCP).
</P>
<P>
The three opposition parties criticized the cabinet for its
deflationary economic policy, poor handling of bad loans,
insufficient administrative reform, political corruption, and lack
of progress in talks on the reversion of the U.S. Marine Futemma
Air Station in Okinawa Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
If a no-confidence motion is passed, it would force the
Japanese prime minister to resign or to dissolve the lower house
for a new election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
