<HEADLINE> Old Rivals Belgium, Netherlands to Clash Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Belgium and old rivals the Netherlands
will again face each other in the same group at the soccer World Cup
finals but the outcome of their Saturday clash at the Stade de France
is hard to predict.
</P>
<P>
Belgium is hoping to repeat their 1-0 victory over their geographic
neigbour at the last World Cup in the United States four years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Belgium has failed to win since then, losing to the
Orange Legion twice in the European qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
Their effort this time in Group E was greatly hamstrung by the
dropping of veteran Enrico Scifo, the 32-year-old midfielder who
played a key-role four years ago.
</P>
<P>
A rift between coach George Leekens and Scifo, developed after the
Anderlecht midfielder was left out of a March friendly, was apparently
widening.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Netherlands, quarterfinalist at last World
Cup, has to rest their key striker Dennis Bergkamp on the bench for
most time of the opening encounter.
</P>
<P>
The English Footballer of the Year, haunted by an injury inflicted
at the English FA Cup final, is unlikely to play the full 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Captain Frank de Boer, however, becomes coach Gus Hiddink's another
injury worry after twisting his ankle in training earlier this week.
</P>
