<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Corporate Failures Rise Sharply in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The number of Japan's corporate
bankruptcies shot up 37.5 percent in May from a year earlier to
1,791, the highest monthly figure since 1984, a private credit
research agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
May was the 12th straight month in which corporate failures
with debts of 10 million yen (about 69,430 U.S. dollars) or more
rose from a year earlier, and the third in a row in which the
number topped 1,700, Teikoku Databank said.
</P>
<P>
Of the failed companies, 70.7 percent blamed the prolonged
economic slump to their bankruptcy, the agency said in a monthly
report on corporate failures.
</P>
<P>
Total debts left by the failed companies increased 55.5 percent
from a year earlier to 780.68 billion yen (about 5.4 billion
dollars), a record monthly high.
</P>
<P>
The agency predicted that large-scale corporate failures could
follow in view of the increase in bankruptcies among small and
midsize companies.
</P>
<P>
"Increased bankruptcies among small and midsize companies are a
prelude to large-scale corporate bankruptcies," it said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said intensified deflationary pressure is causing an
increase in inventories despite production cuts.
</P>
<P>
All industries saw double-digit increases in corporate failures
from the previous year for the fourth consecutive month, with the
construction, manufacturing and wholesale industries the hardest
hit, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
