<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Trade Deficit Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Israel's trade deficit dropped
by a dramatic 36 percent on an annualized basis from November 1997
to May 1998, thanks to expanded exports and shrunk imports.
</P>
<P>
The deficit was 425 million U.S. dollars in May, the Jerusalem
Post newspaper reported Friday, quoting figures released by the
Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The exports totaled 1.78 billion dollars, up 14 percent in
annual terms from November 1997 to May 1998 and imports 2.23
billion dollars, a decrease of 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
About 47 percent of all imports in May were raw materials, and
74 percent of the exports were industrial products and software,
23 percent diamonds and 3 percent agriculture goods.
</P>
<P>
The declining trade deficit along with the increase of imports
of investment goods have seemed to reinforce Finance Minister
Ya'acov Neeman's claim that Israel is nearing the end of its
economic stagnation.
</P>
<P>
The imports of investment goods went up 9 percent in the
March-May period after slumping by 10 percent from September 1997
to February 1998.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Israel's Economist Intelligence Unit predicted
that Israel will see a only 0.9 percent economic growth this year,
the lowest since 1966, due to the continuing tumble in tourism and
investment arising from the ongoing Asian crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
