<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rally on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Share prices rallied on the
Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index
(STII) reversed its downward trend to rise by 4.66 points to close
at 1,091.49 points Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that although stock prices ended slightly higher,
the market remained concerned over Asia's economic crisis and the
overnight drop on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the Dow's fall reinforced fears that Asian
economies would ultimately take a toll on the Western economies if
recovery proves a long-drawn affair.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume fell marginally to 123.89 million units,
valued at 264.39 million Singapore dollars (151.95 million U.S.
dollars). Declines continued to overwhelm advances by 200 to 82,
while 308 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Land was the most actively
traded stock as it registered a turnover of 12.53 million units.
It was followed by Magnum which had 8.79 million shares traded.
UOB (United Overseas Bank) Foreign was next with 5.9 million
shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
GP Battery led the gainers of the day as it rose by 32 cents to
finish at 3.08 Singapore dollars. SPH (Singapore Press Holdings)
increased by 30 cents to end at 12.9 Singapore dollars. Local car
distributor Cycle &AMP; Carriage (C&AMP;C) was up 16 cents to close at
4.22 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, local computer sound card maker Creative 50
was the biggest loser as it declined by 6.1 dollars to end at 20.9
Singapore dollars. City Developments warrant98 fell by 56 cents to
close at 1.78 Singapore dollars, while Khong Guan lost 50 cents to
finish at 2.1 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
