<HEADLINE> Malaysia Gets Peace-Keeping Vehicles Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will bring back the
support vehicles used in peace-keeping in Bosnia-Herzegovina and
offered by the British government to Malaysia for free, Defense
Minister Syed Hamid Albar said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The vehicles, worth about 26 million ringgit (6.5 million U.S.
dollars) were lent to Malaysia's peace-keeping force to carry out
its duties in Bosnia-Herzegovina under the United Nations banner
and were now offered to Malaysia for free, he said in Lumut, some
290 kilometers northwest from here, where he inspected a parade by
members of the Royal Malaysian Navy (RMN) Reserve Corps.
</P>
<P>
"The government decided to bring back the vehicles after taking
into account that it would cost 30 million ringgit (7.5 million
dollars) if we were to buy them and only about 2 million ringgit
(500,000 dollars) to ship them back," he was quoted by the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry would use special flights and Malaysia
International Shipping Corporation (MISC) ships to bring back the
last Malaysian peace-keeping force -- Malcon V and the vehicles in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of the Malcon V troops, comprising 795 officers
and men, who had served in Bosnia-Herzegovina since last December
1, returned home Thursday, and the last batch would arrive on July
10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
