<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Gulf War Victims Get 45 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is to receive the
biggest compensation package of 45.387 million U.S. dollars in
the second half of this year, for expatriate Sri Lankans who lost
their jobs during the Gulf War, according to Labor Ministry
sources here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Sri Lankan Labor Minister W. D.J. Seneviratne
had held talks with the executive secretary of United Nations
Compensation Commission (UNCC) and the compensation package was a
result of the talks with the high officials of the UNCC.
</P>
<P>
The minister had successfully discussed the problems faced by
those who had lost employment in Kuwait during the 1990-91 Gulf
War and the present package will be disbursed among 18,000 Sri
Lankans, mostly women, some of whom were in dire straits and a
majority of whom were without employment, the sources noted.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka received 33 million U.S. dollars this year and last
year it received two installments of 15.9 million dollars in
March and an additional 48.8 million dollars in December.
</P>
<P>
There reportedly were about 100,000 Sri Lankan workers in
Kuwait before the Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
