<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Announces Policy Toward Eritreans Living </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian government said
Friday that its policy toward 550,000 Eritreans now residing in
Ethiopia "remains intact" and the Eritreans "can continue to live
and work peacefully in Ethiopia."
</P>
<P>
However, the office of the Ethiopian government spokesperson
said in a news release, "Some who are in leadership positions in
security sensitive posts - such as telecommunications and the
electricity company - must take one month's enforced leave." But
"they can stay in the country," it added.
</P>
<P>
The leadership of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front,
which has a party office in Addis Ababa, must leave the country
but their families have a choice to stay if they wish to, said
the news release.
</P>
<P>
Referring to an office of the Eritrean Community Organization
(COM), the news release said, "The leadership of COM must leave
but their families have the choice to stay."
</P>
<P>
"Some Eritrean individuals who have been raising money for the
war while residing in Ethiopia and have been involved in spying
activities must leave the country," the news release said, adding
"Their possessions will not be confiscated and they can nominate
an agent to look after them."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the air raid on Adigrat in northern Ethiopia which
took place at 17:30 local time Thursday, killed four people and
wounded 30 civilians. A grain store of the Disaster Prevention
and Preparedness Commission was also damaged during the raid,
according to the office of the Ethiopian government spokesperson.
</P>
</TEXT>
