<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Post First Rise in Nine Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
staged a dramatic comeback in late trading to post its first rise
in nine days Friday as buyers moved in on bargain-priced major
stocks.
</P>
<P>
The market had started weaker after a big fall in gold and
mining stocks and a poor lead from the United States market, but a
solid afternoon recovery after a move upwards by the Australian
dollar meant the all ordinaries index ended 13 points higher at
2,571.7.
</P>
<P>
"The fund managers are buying the banks, they are buying the
yielders," Stuart Smith from Henderson Charlton Jones said.
</P>
<P>
The late afternoon turnaround ended an eight day streak of
lower closes on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 37 points to 4,474.6, led by a
stunning rise in the stock price of global media giant News Corp.
Its ordinary shares soared 77 cents to 10.56 Australian dollars
while its preferred shares jumped 55.9 cents to 9.10 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications giant Telstra also received support Friday,
with its installment receipts rising seven cents to 3.65
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were steady to marginally higher, with Westpac
Bank's nine cent rise to 9.57 Australian dollars the best
performance of the majors.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was 4.8 cents stronger at 21.053
Australian dollars, ANZ Bank was unmoved at 10.62 Australian
dollars and the Commonwealth Bank of Australia had a five cent
rise to 17.45 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished down 8.6 points at 1,042.6 on
the back of lower commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
The major diversified resources concerns all had falls. Rio
Tinto closed down 24.1 cents to 19.259 Australian dollars. BHP
ended down 12 cents at 13.23 Australian dollars despite rumors in
the foreign exchange market that a multinational company was
buying Australian dollars in order to launch a takeover bid for
the resources giant.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks received a pasting, with the index dropping 35.4
points to 1,089.8 as the bullion price fell 5.95 U.S. dollars per
ounce to 287.70 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover Friday was 377.92 million shares at a value
of 1.24 billion Australian dollars (744 million U.S. dollars),
with falls outnumbering rises at 805 to 488. 
</P>
</TEXT>
