<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Stock Exchange Boss Calls for Amended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The current legal and regulatory
framework in the Lusaka Stock Exchange (LUSE) market has retarded
investor confidence and impeded capital market growth,
LUSE General Manager Charles Mate has said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Friday quoted him as saying in Lusaka that
the Securities Act has major flaws against a modern and
progressive stock exchange market.
</P>
<P>
"This situation requests immediate redress to ensure the
growth of LUSE market and success in winning investor confidence
and competitive advantage," said Mate.
</P>
<P>
A successful legal framework for a modern clearing and
settlement system should have clear definition of property
interests, mechanisms for asset segregation and protection of
investors'assets, he said.
</P>
<P>
The regulatory framework should be clear, transparent and
designed to include aspects such as monitoring and compliance,
comprehensive description of regulatory jurisdiction and
relationship among players in the market.
</P>
<P>
He tabulated a number of factors that are urgently required in
the capital market legislation to make any headway including the
recognition of LUSE central share depository where shareholders'
assets are managed by LUSE rather than having physical licences.
</P>
<P>
Legislation should also allow LUSE to transfer settlements of
assets into shareholders' accounts, allow the movement of assets
from seller's account to buyer's account at the stock exchange
and recognize nominee name and accounts as he plays the
intermediary between the issuer/registrar and the beneficial
owner.
</P>
<P>
Mate also called for the legal structure that will harmonize
the companies act, the bank and financial services act and the
competition and fair trading act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
