<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Contributes Spreading of Rodent-Borne Illness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- El Nino phenomenon may have
boosted the population of rodents capable of spreading an often
fatal respiratory illness in the southwestern United States.
</P>
<P>
The warm ocean current was believed behind the increased
rainfall last winter, and the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention (CDCP) warned Thursday against its health effect.
</P>
<P>
El Nino causes "winter rain and moderate temperatures, which
increase a type of grass that is fed on by rodents," said Dr. Ali
Khan, of the CDCP's National Center for Infectious Diseases.
</P>
<P>
In turn, said the CDCP, the number of rodents potentially
carrying hantaviruses has jumped 10 to 20 fold during the past
year in the states of Arizona, Colorado and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
That boost increases the potential for the viruses, in the
urine, droppings and saliva of deer mice, white-footed mice,
cotton rats and rice rats, to be transmitted to humans through air.
</P>
<P>
There have been 183 confirmed cases of hantavirus pulmonary
syndrome in 29 states since the first outbreak of the virus, named
after a river in South Korea, in the U.S. southwest in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
Of those cases on the record, 43.7 percent were fatal.
</P>
<P>
The most recent cases occurred in Colorado and New Mexico
during the second half of April, the CDCP said. Two of the three
people who developed the illness died.
</P>
<P>
Early symptoms of hantavirus pulmonary syndrome include
fatigue, fever and muscle aches. Some patients also experience
headaches, dizziness, chills and nausea, vomiting or diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
Later symptoms include coughing and difficult breathing caused
by fluid buildup in the lungs. Researchers believe initial
symptoms occur one to five weeks after exposure to the virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
