<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Weak Yen Inflicts Pain on Asian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A weak yen has been dragging down
other Asian currencies further this week, stirring fresh concerns
that the Japanese currency's slide would inflict new pain on the
Asian region.
</P>
<P>
The yen fell to over 144 against the U.S. dollar Friday, the
lowest in eight years. During the week, the sliding yen has not
only dragged down other Asian currencies to their new lows in
months, but also shattered the stocks in the region.
</P>
<P>
A weak yen has cast a shadow over the recovery prospects of the
battered Asian economy since the depreciation of the Japanese
currency would severely hurt exports of other Asian countries,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
The continuous tumble of the yen would affect the export growth
of Asian countries in two ways, they said.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, it makes Japanese companies more formidable
competitors in the world export markets.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, for other Asian nations that sell directly to Japan,
their products would become less attractive to Japanese consumers.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the weak yen would limit the chances for
Asian companies, especially those Japanese companies' competitors
in South Korea and China's Taiwan province, to get rid of their
economic woes by increasing exports.
</P>
<P>
A weak yen also means that Japan could hardly suck in enough
exports from other Asian countries to help them recover from the
11-month-old regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, export growth in Southeast Asian
countries has actually declined because of a lack of bank
financing and weak Japanese demand.
</P>
<P>
Now, the depreciation of the yen has made the prospects for
export growth of other Asian nations bleaker.
</P>
<P>
The weak yen has also raised worries that a new round of
financial crisis might hit the region, if the Japanese government
fails to check the yen's downturn.
</P>
<P>
To prevent a new free fall of their currencies, Asian central
banks would have to maintain high interest rates, intensifying the
sharp downturn in domestic demand and further squeezing local
banks and hard-pressed borrowers.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, slow economic growth, more company closures and
more lay-offs would follow in the Asian countries that have been
hit by the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Besides, for Asian companies that rely on Japanese capital to
operate, a cutback in lending by Japanese banks in response to the
yen's slide would also worsen an already suffocating credit
crunch.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, as the weak yen reflects Japan's faltering economy,
its continuous fall would prompt the Japanese to put more of their
capital in more promising investments in the United States and
Europe instead of other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Without enough funds to fuel the development in Asia, the
region's recovery process would take a longer time, experts said.
</P>
<P>
At present, they said, joint intervention by Japan, the United
States and other industrial countries may help keep the yen from
further falling.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States seems reluctant to do so, partly
because it believes that it would be futile given Japan's weak
economy, and partly because it is not persuaded that a new crisis
is imminent.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the yen is most likely to sink further and continue
to drag other Asian currencies down with it next week, economists
said, adding that the yen's downturn would make the Asian economic
prospects gloomier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
