<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Falling Australian Dollar No Help to Wool Industry: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The plunging Australian dollar
would be of little benefit to Australia's wool growers until it
stabilizes, analysts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Wesfarmers Dalgety, a national wool organization, said wool
prices held firm this week in the wake of recent heavy falls due
to the limited supply on offer.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar plunged below 60 U.S. cents this week,
near the lowest level in 12 years, under pressure from a weak
Japanese yen and attacks by international hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator closed four cents higher at 588
Australian cents per kg clean.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar remains low. However, it will be of
little benefit to the wool industry until it stabilizes,"
Wesfarmers said in its Wool Weekly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
"As the dollar continues to weaken, many buyers are holding off
in anticipation of wool becoming cheaper before they begin
buying," it said.
</P>
<P>
Wesfarmers said limited supplies of wool between now and Spring
should bolster the market.
</P>
<P>
It said 45,658 bales were rostered for next week's sales, so
the market was expected to continue to hold firm, with small
increases likely.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Council of Wool Exporters (ACWE) said wool
prices leveled in Sydney but lost ground in west Australia's
coastal city of Fremantle at this week's auction sales.
</P>
<P>
The western market indicator dropped 10 cents to close at 539
Australian cents per kg clean.
</P>
<P>
A total of 43,514 bales were offered for sale, with 21.7
percent passed in.
</P>
<P>
"Although a small offering and high pass-in rates kept the
market level in Sydney this week, exporters expect a weaker market
next week in anticipation of large quantities coming on the market
at the end of June," ACWE said.
</P>
<P>
Sales continue next week in Sydney and south Australia's port
city of Adelaide, with 45,660 bales rostered for sale, down 6,500
bales on the original rostered quantity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
