<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Government to Present Budget for 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government will
present the national budget for fiscal 1998-99 in the National
Assembly Friday afternoon focusing on self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
This will be the second national budget of the present
government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif since it came to
power after an overwhelming victory in the general elections in
February last year.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the budget for fiscal 1998-99 will envisage
concrete measures in line with Sharif's avowed policy of
self-reliance to counter the economic challenges faced by Pakistan
after its nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The federal cabinet is expected to give approval to the budget
proposals at its meeting Friday before they are presented in the
National Assembly late in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The main thrust of the forthcoming budget will be on
self-reliance, broadening of tax base, and checking of tax
evasion.
</P>
<P>
The budget is being presented in the backdrop of economic
sanctions imposed by some Western nations in the wake of
Pakistan's detonation of nuclear devices late last month.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Sharif has instructed the
policy-makers to ensure minimum burden on the common men, while
making necessary adjustment in taxation proposals.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the impact of possible economic sanctions, and more
importantly, to move towards the cherished goal of self-reliance,
the new budget will focus on "breaking the begging bowl" and
"relying on one's own means."
</P>
<P>
Last year, when the government led by the Pakistan Muslim
League (N) presented its first budget after assuming power in
February, it was facing an uphill task of salvaging an economy
which was in shambles.
</P>
<P>
The new budget is also likely to see stringent measures against
the chronic loan defaulters as all incentives to recover stuck-up
loans had fallen short of the desired results.
</P>
<P>
An economic survey for 1997-98 released by the government
Wednesday reflected realization of the twin objectives of
marcoeconomic stabilization and a comfortable GDP growth rate.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey showed mixed trends in Pakistan's economy,
including a 5.4 percent GDP growth rate, a 5 percent fiscal
deficit, a single-digit inflation rate and a serious revenue
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
The new budgetary proposals are likely to be adopted by the
National Assembly on June 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
