<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 500,000 Dollar Cheques Stolen from Zambian Copper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-one cheques worth 1.1
billion Kwacha (about 500,000 U.S.Dollars) were stolen from
the accounts department at the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM) in Kitwe, forcing the mines' management to issue a stop
payment order to banks.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia Friday quoted some staff of the ZCCM as
confirming that the 31 Cheques were stolen from the ZCCM last week
and a police unit is investigating the matter.
</P>
<P>
The disappearance of the cheques is believed to a racket in
which some workers allegdly smuggled cheques which they paid to
some of the suppliers of the ZCCM, said the staff.
</P>
<P>
They said that the "culprits" issued the cheques to the
suppliers without consent of their supervisors and received
commissions in return.
</P>
<P>
"The people involved took advantage of the situation and
smuggled out these cheques to their favored suppliers in returen
for commissions," they said.
</P>
<P>
The racket was discovered when some of the cheques bounced and
the management was surprised because it had not issued the cheques.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM earns Zambia more than 80 percent of its foreign exchange
earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
