<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Reduces Army to 33,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing re-organization of the
Zimbabwe national army has seen the 51,000-strong force being
reduced to 33,000 since the exercise started in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The army will be further reduced when the authorities see fit,
said Minister of Defense Moven Mahachi in an interview with the
Daily Herald on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Some members of the force were being retrenched or retired to
enable new recruitment, Mahachi said.
</P>
<P>
However, all these will remain a reserve force and can be
called upon if the need arises, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi said, "We will reduce the size of the army further so
that recruitment can take place. We need new blood, just like in
any other organisation."
</P>
<P>
On the proposed establishment of a Southern African
Development Community (SADC) peacekeeping brigade, Mahachi said
Zimbabwe's army is supportive of the idea.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that any foreign country wanting to help
should do so within the framework of SADC.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a number of developed countries
want to be involved in the setting up of the brigade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
