<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians See Four Films Each Year: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Australians are going to the
movies more often but have fewer cinema chains to choose from,
figures released Friday by the Australian Bureau of Statistics
(ABS) show.
</P>
<P>
The average Australian pay to see four films a year, spending
more than 480 million U.S. dollars in the process, with the number
of paid admissions to cinemas rising 22 percent in the three years
to June 1997, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
But the number of businesses in the industry was dropping, with
16 percent fewer in June 1997 than three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
The industry is dominated by eight motion picture businesses,
each of which had an income greater than 4.8 million U.S. dollars,
the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
Australia has 325 cinemas and 28 drive-ins, with a total of
1,050 picture screens around the country, mainly concentrated in
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
The industry employs 7,739 people, up 35 percent since June
1994.
</P>
<P>
Businesses in the motion picture industry earned 499 million
U.S. dollars during 1996-97, of which 66 percent were from box
office takings, the ABS said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese TV Manufacturers Locked In "Service War" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- After a heated "price war" in 1996
and 1997, Chinese manufacturers of televisions are now trying for
a bigger market share by engaging in a "service battle".
</P>
<P>
The battle was started, market analysts say, when sellers cut
the price of well-known foreign brands of televisions like Sony
and National, at a time when Chinese manufacturers had no room to
cut prices further, so they turned to service as the next weapon.
</P>
<P>
After careful consideration, executives at the TCL Television
Company say they believe that it is more effective to increase
spending on service by 0.5 percent than to bringing the price down
by 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Haier, another major Chinese brand, has been offering what it
calls "five-star" service, while its close competitor, Konka, has
introduced free at-home service.
</P>
<P>
TCL was then inspired to even keep files for its clients and
provide 24-hour service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
