<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, June 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- India has rejected proposals of United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan to send his special envoy to New
Delhi and Islamabad to talk about all contentious issues
including Kashmir between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief was said to have talked with Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif Wednesday and said he would send a special
envoy to both countries to discuss their contentious issues.
(India-UN Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivorad Jovanovic has
reiterated that the Kosovo issue should only be resolved through
political dialogue within the Republic of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug news agency reported Thursday that Jovanovic called the
Kosovo crisis a terrorist act by Albanian splittists. Jovanovic
denied the existence of a massive cleansing of ethnic Albanians by
Serbs. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Any action threatening political and social
stability in the reform process in Indonesia would not be
tolerated, local press Friday quoted The Armed Forces' (ABRI's)
Commander Wiranto as saying.
</P>
<P>
"ABRI's political stance toward the reform process is very
clear and firm. The reform process must be constitutional,
consistent, in the right direction, peaceful and orderly," Wiranto
said in his report to President B.J. Habibie during a ceremony at
the Presidential Palace here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He warned that unruly demonstrations and protests in the
country would be crushed. (Indonesia-Stability)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The scarcity of water, especially in Africa,
the Middle East and Southeast Asia, is one of world's top
environmental challenges, a release from the United Nations said
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The release said a third of the world's population lives in
areas where lack of water limits development, and in 20 years,
two-thirds of the world's population will live in areas where
development is constrained because of water scarcity. (UN
Report-Water Scarcity)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank approved three loans on Thursday,
totaling the evivalent of 496 million U.S. dollars, for
development projects in Mexico, Colombia and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The first loan valued at 400 million dollars is for Mexico's
second contractual saving development program. (World
Bank-LATAM-Loans)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Intel, the world's largest chip-maker, said it
would release faster versions of a number of its processors in the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
"We are currently selling as high as a 400 MHz product, and
within a matter of weeks you will see a 450 MHz product
introduced," Gordon Casey, director of investor relations for
Intel, told a conference in Minneapolis Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 450 MHz version will soon be Intel's flagship Pentium II
chip, largely the standard for personal computers priced above
1,200 U.S. dollars. (US-Intel-New Chips) 
</P>
</TEXT>
