<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Province Using Overseas Funds for Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The agriculture sector of
China's Guangdong Province has become a new investment spot for
overseas investors, partly owing to the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
A number of overseas investors have shifted their focus to
agriculture, which has lower risk but higher returns.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, the province added 26
overseas-funded agriculture projects worth nearly 54 million US
dollars, both of them a more than 44 percent increase from the
same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The increased spending has helped the local opening up of
agriculture, which now has investors from 20 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The province has developed a series of measures to
internationalize local agricultural development by building
overseas-funded pilot zones, improving infrastructure, training
personnel, and providing technology and services.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is situated close to Hong Kong, Macao, and Southeast
Asia, and has distinct advantages for export-oriented
agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
