<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Community in HK Marks Centennial of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine community living
in Hong Kong celebrated Friday the 100th anniversary of the
Philippines' declaration of independence from Spanish colonial
rule.
</P>
<P>
There are around 160,000 Filipinos living in the city, of whom
140,000 are domestic helpers.
</P>
<P>
A red marker was unveiled Friday afternoon on Morrison Hill
Road, Wanchai, to commemorate the birth of the Philippines' first
national flag in Hong Kong 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The flag was handmade by Philippine patriots, one of them a
seven-year-old girl, in May 1898 in the residence of Felipe
Agoncillo, the first Philippine diplomat, said Consul-General of
the Philippines Estrella Berenguel.
</P>
<P>
The flag was brought back to the Philippines and raised on June
12, 1898, when General Emilio Aguinaldo, the first Philippine
president, declared independence in Cavite province, south of
Manila, she told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The flag, designed by General Aguinaldo himself, has blue and
red stripes and a white triangle, enclosing a gold "Sun of
Liberty" with eight rays and three five-pointed gold stars, one in
each corner. The flag is now kept by the family of General
Aguinaldo.
</P>
<P>
Centennial celebrations will last the whole day, according to a
spokesman for the Philippine Consulate General. From a national
flag raising ceremony in the morning to the unveiling of the
marker in the afternoon to a grand reception hosted by the
consulate general and a party open to the public in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) Tung Chee Hwa will attend the reception, he said.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang departed Thursday for Manila
to attend the Philippine centennial celebrations on behalf of the
SAR government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Rescuing Human Gene Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are making an
effort to save human gene resources in a nationwide operation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese geneticists said recently that human gene resources
need to be protected through a coordinated effort.
</P>
<P>
The news came at a national symposium on genetic resources
collection sponsored by the Ministry of Science and Technology and
Ministry of Health's China Biological Engineering Center.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 1.2 billion people including 55 ethnic
groups, and a large amount of genetic isolation groups and many
types of diseases. In some remote areas, scientists have found
many members belonging to one family by blood concentrated in a
locality that is good for developing human genetic resources and
for new genes for dealing with diseases.
</P>
<P>
A state genetics lab was established at Hunan Medical
University in 1991 which has cloned 9 human genes. It has also
established a data bank of Chinese disease types that has a cell
bank of chromosome mutation of the Chinese and a DNA sample bank.
</P>
<P>
Xia Jiahui, head of the lad, says that by April the lab had 31
types of diseases. The lab has also established 444 cell strains
and 2,137 DNA samples.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
