<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeastern Chinese Grain Producer Using New Type Of Manure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Heilongjiang Province, a major
Chinese grain producer, is spreading the use of a new type of
manure that makes crops mature faster and increases output and is
better for the soil.
</P>
<P>
The new active bacteria manure uses decayed moss, a certain
kind of coal, and other organic compounds and takes in
microorganisms as it ferments, according to Qu Jichun, an engineer
at the Provincial Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang is rich in organic matter, with a fifth of China's
total amount of peat. The science academy experimented with these
resources and developed seven kinds of bacterial manure after a
dozen years of research.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province produced 2,000 tons of compound manure
which was used on 2,930 ha of experimental plots. The bio-manure
has been applied to 8,000 ha of land in the province so far this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
