<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Using Technology To Produce Traditional Chinese Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Advanced technology is now being
used by a company in east China's Shandong Province to replace
older methods of producing the traditional Chinese
medicine 'donkey-hide gelatin', to improve both quality and
quantity.
</P>
<P>
Donkey-hide gelatin, or E-gelatin, is made by boiling a donkey
hide and refining the results to use it as a blood tonic. The
gelatin is referred to as Dong'e E-gelatin, after its place of
origin, Shandong's Dong'e County.
</P>
<P>
Previously, most of this work was done by hand. Then, in the
1980s, the Shandong Dong'e E-gelatin Group, China's largest
E-gelatin producer, started using technology to condense the
E-gelatin, shortening the production cycle from 60 days to 30
days. And, the microwave drying equipment the group used took 6 more
days off the production cycle.
</P>
<P>
The group also began using computer controls to increase the
ratio of quality products from 55 percent to 86 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the January-April period this year, it had 57.9 million yuan
in sales, up 23 percent from the same period last year and its
pre-tax profits increased by 52 percent to 20.6 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Its products are also being exported to ten countries and
regions, including the U.S., Japan and Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Urged to Be More Responsible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Leading Singapore newspapers
Friday urged Japan to be more responsible and to do much more to
avoid triggering a new round of Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial, the Lianhe Zaobao, published in Chinese, said
the depreciation of the Japanese yen has brought "snow plus frost'
effect to the Asian economy which has been already battered.
</P>
<P>
Citing a Chinese proverb that "let the mischief-maker undo the
mischief," the paper urged Japan to shoulder more responsibility
and take positive measures to stabilize its currency.
</P>
<P>
The English newspaper The Straits Times said in a commentary
that "a weak yen to boost Japanese exports will hit other Asian
countries, which are doing their damnedest to pump up exports as a
way out of their financial miseries."
</P>
<P>
The paper proposed that Asian leaders get together and explore
what they can do collectively to restore confidence in the region,
and send strong signals to the capital markets that Asian leaders
are taking collective action to address some of their problems.
</P>
<P>
"Instead of letting the yen fall to jumpstart an anemic
Japanese economy, Tokyo could take stronger steps to reflate it,"
the paper stressed.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Japanese have already put up several fiscal
packages including April's offering of 128 billion U.S. dollars in
tax cuts and public works spending to boost domestic demand, the
paper said that "this has proved insufficient."
</P>
<P>
"Which suggests that more, much more has to be done," the paper
highlighted.
</P>
<P>
The paper also noted that there are rooms for Japan to take
other moves to complement fiscal stimulus.
</P>
<P>
The paper also warned that competitive devaluation is a policy
that is "ultimately self-defeating."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen had been sliding downhill steadily for more
than two months and finally collapsed Monday through the barrier
of 140-yen against the U.S. dollar, hitting its lowest point in
seven years and breaching a psychologically crucial level.
</P>
<P>
The yen's unabated fall has made the region suffering and is
threatening to spark a new round of Asian financial crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rodman Hit with Second Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Dennis Rodman, star of the
Chicago Bulls, has been sued for the second time in less than a
week, this time by a woman who claimed the NBA player sexually
assaulted her in April at the Las Vegas Hilton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
The complaint was filed Wednesday by Dixie Johnson, a Clark
County resident.
</P>
<P>
"On April 19, 1998, inside of the Las Vegas Hilton Hotel and
Casino, defendant, without cause, consent or provocation, sexually
assaulted plaintiff by physically grabbing her left breast and
shaking it," the federal lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
It claims Rodman's actions violated the federal Violence
Against Women Act. Johnson is seeking compensatory damages of
300,000 U.S. dollars and punitive damages of 3 million dollars,
plus attorney fees and costs of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, James Brasich, a craps dealer, filed a lawsuit
against Rodman in District Court, claiming the basketball player
humiliated him at work in October by rubbing his bald head,
stomach and groin with the dice before rolling them.
</P>
<P>
Brasich is seeking 300,000 dollars in compensatory and punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
Richard Howell, Rodman's lawyer, said:."These kinds of
allegations against individuals like Dennis Rodman at some level
come with the territory. It's something we've dealt with in the
past. We've been successful in the past and we have every
confidence we will be successful in the future."
</P>
<P>
Rodman, a famous and notorious figure in NBA, stole the
attention yesterday in Game 4 when he shot in 5 of 6 ball at the
line in the final minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
