<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading U.S. Semiconductor-maker Reports Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A leading U.S. semiconductor
company Thursday reported a fiscal fourth quarter loss due to a
drop in sales for personal computers and networking products.
</P>
<P>
National Semiconductor Corp., based in Santa Clara, California,
said its revenues fell from quarterly 652 million dollars a year
ago to 510 million U.S. dollars in the quarter that ended May 31.
</P>
<P>
The company also reported a net loss of 69.3 million dollars
for the fourth quarter, compared with a profit of 57.4 million
dollars in the year-earlier fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
"Current weekly order rates suggest that the market decline may
be bottoming out," Brian Halla, National Chief Executive, said in
a statement. "But visibility is limited and the outlook for the
current quarter is essentially flat with the fourth quarter."
</P>
<P>
North American market, National said, was the most affected by
the decline in orders, followed by Southeast Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The fourth quarter sales of analog products, led by power and
data acquisition devices, improved from weakness in the third
quarter but declined from a year ago, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
