<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyundai Founder to Enter DPRK Via Panmunjon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Chung Joo-young, founder and
honorary chairman of the Hyundai Group, will enter the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on June 16 through Panmunjon,
said South Korea's Ministry of Unification on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chung will be South Korea's first businessman to enter the DPRK
through the armistice village of Panmunjon since the Korean
peninsula was divided into two parts in 1945.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by his brothers and sons, Chung will go to the DPRK
for the purpose of hometown visit and consultation for economic
cooperation, including a tourism project of Mountain Kumkang at
the invitation of the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"The permission of Mr. Chung's visit to the North was in
accordance with the Measures for the Promotion of the Inter-Korean
Economic Cooperation, enacted on April 30, 1998," said the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Chung, visited the DPRK once in 1989, will take with him 50
trucks loaded with 500 cows in this visit.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, Chung, whose hometown is now the DPRK's
Tongchon, announced he would donate 1,000 heads of cattle to the
famine-ridden DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"I will drive the cattle into the North through Panmunjon
within a month. North Koreans can use the cattle as they please,"
the 83-year-old business tycoon said.
</P>
<P>
The 500 cattle will be delivered to the DPRK at Tongilgak on
the DPRK's side of Panmunjon through the (South) Korean National
Red Cross (KNRC) and the 50 trucks will be given to the DPRK in
terms of credit.
</P>
<P>
Another 500 cows will be transported to the DPRK after
inter-Korean consultations.
</P>
<P>
"Upon the fact that the visitors and the KNRC aid of 500 cows
use Panmunjon for their trip, the government of the Republic of
Korea hopes the inter-Korean relations progress further," said the
Ministry of Unification in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
