<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Scientists Becoming Shareholders (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- There used to be a popular saying
in China which goes as "those who make guided missiles earn less
than the ones who sell eggs boiled in tea", a vivid portrayal of a
strange phenomenon that lasted into the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
Even then, technicians received no reward for their scientific
research discoveries and lived on skimpy salaries with no other
source of income, while less educated people were making big money
in the wake of the country's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
This is no longer the case. "Knowledge is power, technology is
knowledge, and in present-day China, knowledge means wealth,"
commented a noted sociologist.
</P>
<P>
The expert pointed to the fact as a growing number of Chinese
scientists and research personnel have become shareholders of
companies they work for and contribute their research findings to
as a form of investment.
</P>
<P>
The Dongjiang Group, northeast China's Liaoning Province, for
example, is a data-processing company with 200 million yuan in
fixed assets, in Liaoning Province, which recently gave a fifth of
its 50 million shares to a dozen technicians as a reward for their
outstanding work.
</P>
<P>
Li Peiying, chairman of the board of directors, explains, "I
have no regret about giving out such a large amount of shares to
technicians as the move closely ties company interests to those of
the technicians and encourages them to be more creative."
</P>
<P>
In this age of fierce market competition, he says, the key to a
company's success is to be always in the forefront of science."
</P>
<P>
Wang Xuan, head of the Research Institute of Beijing
University's Founder Group, says that his institute will provide
100 scientists opportunities to become wealthy by introducing the
concept of "technology for shares".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Scientist Become Shareholders (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Only a decade ago, Wang got no remuneration when he developed
computer technology for Chinese character phototypesetting that
now accounts for 70 percent of the market shares in China and has
been exported to Europe and many countries in Asia. It is worth an
estimated 2.5 billion yuan in sales.
</P>
<P>
"My company offered a fitting financial reward for my
contributions. But I didn't expect to take it at that time," Wang
recalls.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of Science and Technology official attributes this
welcome change to the growing respect for knowledge and
professionals in Chinese society. An earnest government effort to
protect intellectual property rights and to commercialize
scientific developments has also encouraged the "technology for
shares", she says.
</P>
<P>
Chinese government departments have passed laws to protect
software, patents, and contracts, while local governments have
said at local trade fairs that they welcome Chinese and foreign
technicians to contribute to local economic growth by providing
their research findings and getting stock in return.
</P>
<P>
And, Chinese scientists and technicians have shown an interest
in becoming shareholders. When the Science and Technology Ministry
and the State Administration for Industry and Commerce came up
with their "Regulation on Questions Relating to Contributing New
and High Technology Research Findings as Shares", quite a number
of technicians asked for copies of the regulation and related
materials.
</P>
<P>
A more expanded view is expressed by Liu Yuhui, a shareholder
of Alpine Software Ltd. in Liaoning Province, who says, "The
practice of 'technology for shares' allows a technician to have a
sense of accomplishment. The interests of individuals is in direct
proportion to the development of their companies."
</P>
<P>
Gu Haibing, a professor at People's University of China says
that this 'technology for shares' trend makes researchers more
enthusiastic but it also results in greater respect for knowledge
and increased family input in education. So, it is important for
improving China's economy and national strength. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
