<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Outlook in Second Half Not Optimistic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Hopes of booming exports in
Thailand are slim in the second half of this year, and the
country's exports will show small, or in the worst case, no growth
at all over the first half, exporters said.
</P>
<P>
Four groups of exporters -- electrical appliances and
electronics, vehicles and parts, plastic pellets and products, and
tableware -- met Commerce Ministry officials on Thursday to study
the export performance for the second half, the Bangkok Post
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Exporters agreed to the revision of export growth for 1998 to
only 1-2 percent in terms of the U.S. dollar from the earlier
estimated 7.1 percent, and the revision of export target to about
57 billion dollars from 62 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The revision stemmed from a significant drop in exports in the
first two months of this year which fell by 2.7 percent to 17
billion dollars compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Karun Kittisataporn, director-general of
the Business Economics Department, as saying that exporters had
complained that fundamental export problems have remained unsolved
such as tight liquidity, high import taxes on raw materials for
the petro-chemical and steel industries, and delays in value-added
tax refunds.
</P>
<P>
Exporters also claimed that their operational costs have soared
due to much higher cargo freight charges by foreign shipping firms
and insufficient containers.
</P>
<P>
Karun said exporters have planned to expand exports to emerging
markets such as East Europe and the Middle East to boost the
overall export value in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
This is in line with the Commerce Ministry's plan to
reinvigorate exports in the second half of the year, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
