<HEADLINE> Clinton's China Trip to Improve Sino-U.S.Ties, Senator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The upcoming visit by U.S.
President Bill Clinton to China will provide a historic
opportunity for the United States to improve its relationship with
China, said U.S. Senator Max Baucus on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Baucus, who will accompany Clinton to China, said that there
are people who want to isolate China, but the result of doing that
would be far worse than working in a constructive manner to make
China a freer, more open society that honors world peace.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the issue of alleged transfers of sensitive
missile technology to China, Baucus warned that these allegations
will hinder potential progress in U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted, "If we turn our back on the Chinese and ostracize
them, then we risk peace in the world. If we extend our hand, as
the world's greatest nation, then we open the door to literally
more than a billion opportunities and secure a better and more
peaceful future for all of our children."
</P>
<P>
Baucus outlined the agenda for the visit. He said the meetings
between Clinton and Chinese leaders will focus on:
</P>
<P>
-- Maintaining a peaceful and strategic relationship in Asia,
working with China to continue the peace there and halting the
spread of nuclear weapons in the region;
</P>
<P>
-- Granting China permanent Most Favored Nation trading status
and prodding China to join the World Trade Organization; and
</P>
<P>
-- Engaging China in addressing environmental problems that
have implications for the entire world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
