<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Foreign Trade Up 12.8 Percent in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's foreign trade including
border trade in the 1997-98 fiscal year ended March totaled 3.24
billion U.S. dollars, a 12.8 percent increase over the previous
fiscal year, according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Of the total trade volume, the export amounted to one billion
dollars, while the import valued at 2.24 billion dollars, said a
current official report on the country's financial, economic and
social conditions issued by the Ministry of National Planning and
Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
Of the export value, which rose by 9.4 percent over the
previous year, the private sector shared 67.8 percent, state
sector 30.2 percent and the cooperative sector 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Despite less export of rice for domestic demand, export of
other commodities such as cotton, jute, beans and pulses, silver
and tin, petroleum products, timber, fish and prawn, and sugar,
increased in the fiscal year especially through the border trade,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Of the export goods, products of agriculture shared 29.9
percent, animal 15.7 percent, forest 21.6 percent, industry 30.1
percent and minerals and gems 2.8 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar imported 14 percent more of the value of goods in the
1997-98 fiscal year than the previous year. Major import items are
capital goods, industrial raw materials, spare parts and consumer
goods, it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the country mostly traded with Asian
countries which accounted for 80.2 percent of its total export
value of 914 million dollars in the last 1996-97. Of that, 46.8
percent deal with Southeast Asian (SEA) countries.
</P>
<P>
Of Myanmar's import value of 1.96 billion dollars in the
1996-97, 86.1 percent are from Asian countries, in which 49.3
percent are from SEA nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
