<HEADLINE> Gas Pipeline Collapses in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A 4.8 kilometer-long pipeline fixed
under the Jamuna Multipurpose Bridge collapsed and fell into the
river Thursday when water was run through it for leakage testing,
a leading English daily here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The gas pipeline, which was anchored underneath the cantilever
slab of the bridge, collapsed at 3:30 AM (local time) Thursday
while being tested, The Daily Star quoted a source of the
Communication Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
It broke down after water was run through it at a certain force
for about twelve hours, he said, adding that the testing was to
continue for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
None was injured in the incident, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The incident would be probed, Communication Minister Anwar
Hossain Manju said when he visited the site Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Company, contractor for the bridge and Gas Transmission
Company of Petrobangla were responsible for the laying of the gas
pipeline along the bridge, the reports added.
</P>
<P>
As the longest bridge in this South Asian country, the Jamuna
Bridge is located in northwest district of Tangail, and it is
being built at a total cost of 900 million U.S. dollars and has
been scheduled to be inaugurated on June 23. 
</P>
