<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Scientists: California Pines Threatened by Killer Fungus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A killer fungus, which causes
the pitch pine's canker, is threatening some species of coastal
pines throughout California, scientists warned.
</P>
<P>
The worst hit is the giant Monterey pine that rises in splendor
from the rolling hills shouldering the Pacific Coast, scientist
said, adding that 80 percent could be destroyed in the next 30
years.
</P>
<P>
Infected trees first go brown at the ends of their branches,
then erupt in sports of oozing pitch and debris. Water and
nutrients are choked off within the tree, and the open infections
allow bark beetles to bore into tree trunks and lay eggs that
hasten the deadly process.
</P>
<P>
"We haven't found any way to stop the disease," Bill Libby, a
tree geneticist for Fletcher Challenge Forestry, told the local
media.
</P>
<P>
California is home to three of the world's five native Monterey
stands. The environmental threat spreads far beyond California.
The Monterey species is the most widely planted non-native tree in
the world, serving as the core of multibillion-dollar timber
industries in Chile, New Zealand and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from Chile, Australia and New Zealand are visiting
California to get a look at the problem, and New Zealand this year
banned all imported pine seeds to try to keep the fungus out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shrimp Farms May Cause Food Crisis in Thailand:Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Water from shrimp farms will gradually seep into the soil and
increase salinity to levels which make rice growing impossible,
today's Nation newspaper quoted the experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
Waste water released from shrimp farms usually has a much
higher level of salinity, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
They explained that salt could contaminate the water and seep
into the soil's texture. Salt from shrimp ponds was found to seep
into water at depths of 600-800 meters underground.
</P>
<P>
Inland shrimp farming has gained popularity in Central Thailand
in the past few years and many rice paddies have been converted.
</P>
<P>
Somsri Arunin, chief of the Soil Salinity Research Group under
the Land Department, said the central region -- with only nine
million rai (1.44 million hectares) of rice paddies -- produces
about seven million tons of the country's total 21 million tons of
rice.
</P>
<P>
"If we allowed prawn farming to continue in the paddy fields,
we will lose the best area for rice growing. And we might soon
face a food crisis," Somsri said.
</P>
<P>
She said it was true that now the impact in the central region
was not clear, but "we will face the problem a few years later
because it takes about five years for salinity to collect in
underground water and soil." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Warning on Eating Raw Oysters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A leading U.S. disease control
organization Thursday warned people not to eat raw or undercooked
shellfish, saying bacteria in the seafood could cause potentially
life-threatening illnesses.
</P>
<P>
The Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDCP) said one
person died and 208 others contracted illnesses from shellfish in
the United States and Canada last summer.
</P>
<P>
All 209 people tested positive for Vibrio Parahaemolyticus,
bacteria commonly found in shellfish which can cause diarrhea,
nausea, stomach cramps and fever. Most patients reported eating
raw oysters and some reported eating mussels, crabs and other
shellfish before falling ill.
</P>
<P>
The oysters had higher-than-normal concentrations of the bacteria,
perhaps because of warmer water in the Pacific Ocean, the CDCP said.
</P>
<P>
The illnesses were reported in California, Oregon, Washington,
Alaska, Hawaii and British Columbia in Canada during July and
August last year.
</P>
<P>
The CDCP recommended cooking shellfish to kill the bacteria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
