<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Admits Laxity in Pursuing Child Labor Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Officials of the United States
Labor Department admitted Thursday that they have not been
vigilant enough in pursuing and punishing repeat offenders against
child labor laws.
</P>
<P>
But while promising to employ new techniques such as using
Internal Revenue Service (IRS) employer identification numbers to
track repeat violators, the officials suggested some of the worst
abuses -- those involving field work picking produce -- won't drop
greatly so long as seasonal farm workers remain so poor.
</P>
<P>
"Children work in agriculture because of poverty,... because
their parents need their contributions to family income," John R.
Fraser, acting director of the Labor Department's wage and hour
division, told a Senate subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
"A majority of farm workers are not covered by the federal
minimum wage, (and) farm work wages in this country have been
stagnant or declining for 20 years," Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show the average annual income for these families is
only 6,000 dollars, compared to nationwide average of 28,000
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Until we deal with those policy questions, we're not going to
come to grips with the problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Clinton administration, Fraser and Gene
Sperling, head of the White House's National Economic Council,
endorsed proposed legislation by Senator Tom Harkin, a Democrat.
The legislation aims at eliminating many exemptions for
agriculture in current child labor laws, increasing fines and
double enforcement spending.
</P>
<P>
However, Senator Mike DeWine, a Republican, who chaired
Thursday's hearing before a Senate subcommittee, criticized the
administration's enforcement of the present law's assessment of
fines for many of the abuses.
</P>
<P>
Fraser said his department has referred several cases to
Justice, but none has been prosecuted since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Fraser was also questioned about a five-part Associated Press
series last December entitled "Children for Hire." In this, AP
reporters spent over five months in finding children working
illegally in 16 states.
</P>
<P>
"We never had the complete list of where the AP believed they
had found child labor violations," Fraser told the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
But asked about the extent of such violations, Fraser said a
study by Rutgers University labor economist Douglas L. Kruse for
the AP, which estimated that 290,200 children worked unlawfully
last year, "is the most comprehensive view currently available."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has requested 800,000 dollars in its
budget for the fiscal year starting October 1 to measure the
extent of child labor abuses in agriculture. DeWine, on Thursday,
asked for a Labor Department report to determine the scope of
abuses in all sectors of the economy and to identify the most
hazardous of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
