<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved three
loans on Thursday, totaling the evivalent of 496 million
U.S. dollars, for development projects in Mexico, Colombia and
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The first loan valued at 400 million dollars is for Mexico's
second contractual saving development program.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to increase the equity, efficiency and
sustainability of the old age security system, limit the fiscal
impact of the current pension system, raise the level of
institutional savings and improve the allocating efficiency of
domestic savings.
</P>
<P>
The second loan of 75 million dollars will be used for
Colombia's urban infrastructure services development project.
</P>
<P>
This project will assist credit market providers for local
public services by strengthening the Local Development Bank's
capacity to offer long-term financing for urban infrastructure
investments.
</P>
<P>
The other loan of 21 million dollars is earmarked for Ecuador's
international trade and integration project. This will enact trade
policy adjustments consistent with Ecuador's World Trade
Organization commitments, and develop new trade agreements for
expanding international market access. 
</P>
