<HEADLINE> Canada Gives Tax Break on Year 2000 Computer Flaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Finance Minister Paul
Martin announced Thursday that small and medium-sized businesses
will get tax relief to address the year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
The relief means the government will provide accelerated
capital cost allowance deductions of up to 34,000 U.S. dollars to
these firms for computer hardware and software to replace old
systems.
</P>
<P>
This will allow them to deduct 100 percent of eligible
expenditures in the year in which they occur.
</P>
<P>
"The year 2000 computer problem presents a serious economic
challenge for the Canadian economy. Businesses must act promptly
if they are going to meet that challenge," Martin said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"That's why we are providing targeted tax relief to help ease
the financial constraints faced by small and medium-sized
businesses in addressing this issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 problem is a design flaw in software applications
and in certain microprocessors related to storage of the year
designation that could play havoc when the calendar year changes
from 1999 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Many software applications such as accounting systems and
certain types of computer hardware could be affected.
</P>
<P>
Many Canadian firms have taken action to ensure that their
computer systems will be ready for the year 2000, but a large
number still have not addressed the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
