<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Finds Childcare Contributes to Longevity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. researchers found that,
among humans and other advanced primates, the sex that provides
more childcare tends to live longer.
</P>
<P>
Dr. John Allman, professor of biology at the California
Institute of Technology, and his colleagues analyzed survival data
for 10 primate species between male and female and looked at the
relationship between lifespan and parenting role.
</P>
<P>
They reported their findings in the latest issue of the
Proceedings of the National Academy of Science.
</P>
<P>
In species where mothers bear primary responsibility for
childcare -- among humans and gorillas, for example -- females
tend to have longer lifespans than males. But in species where
fathers do as much or more of the child-rearing -- such as owl
monkeys and titi monkeys -- males tend to live just as long or
longer than females.
</P>
<P>
"These results run counter to the reasonable expectation that
the increased energy expenditure and risk of falling associated
with carrying an infant would result in increased rather than
decreased mortality," the researchers wrote.
</P>
<P>
The bond between parent and child may play a role in parental
longevity, they suggested. "It is conceivable that the strength
of these bonds and their underlying neurochemical and hormonal
bases might enhance survival."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Remain Largest Rice Exporter in 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will remain the world's
largest rice exporter in the next 10 years, but more should be
done to improve the quality and production, rice experts in
Thailand said.
</P>
<P>
Experts expressed their concern Thursday at a seminar on the
future of Thai rice, organized by the Rice Research Institute of
the Agriculture Ministry.
</P>
<P>
World demand for rice would increase annually through 2025 when
the world population is expected to expand by 1.4 billion, mostly
in Asia, the Bangkok Post Friday quoted Anand Dalodom,
director-general of the Agriculture Department, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Anand said annual rice production in the world would have to be
increased from 560 million tons at present to 840 million tons by
then.
</P>
<P>
Shipping out 19-21 million tons of paddy per year, Thailand
will remain the largest rice exporter for the next 10 years, but
the country must continuously improve its rice quality, he said.
</P>
<P>
Anand noted that of the 60 million rai (9.6 million hectare)
planting area in Thailand, only 20 million rai (3.2 million
hectare) are within irrigated areas, while the rest have to depend
on rain.
</P>
<P>
This is the main factor for the low yields of Thai rice farms,
which average at 300-400 kilograms per rai (0.16 hectare),
compared with an average 900-1,000 kilograms in Japan and South
Korea, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nibhon Wongtra-Ngarn, president of the Thai Rice
Mills Association, also suggested that Thailand should improve its
farm management, currently very poor, and designate rice-planting
zones.
</P>
<P>
He said the Agriculture Ministry should conduct regular surveys
of demand in the world market so that Thailand can improve the
quality of its rice to meet that demand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
