<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Grain Purchase Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji has
signed a decree to promulgate the "Regulations on the Purchase of
Grain."
</P>
<P>
The 23-article regulations govern the purchase of wheat, corn,
rice, and other grains designated by the State Council and by the
governments of various provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
They say that grain purchases are to be done in strict
accordance with state purchase and pricing policies. State ordered
grain prices are to be set as follows: when the market price of
grain is higher than the protective price, the price should be set
with reference to the market price, and when the market price is
lower than the protective price, it should not be lower than the
protective price.
</P>
<P>
State-owned grain companies should buy surplus grain from
farmers according to market prices. But if the market price falls
below the protective price, they should purchase grain at the
protective price.
</P>
<P>
If state-owned grain companies do not have grain storage
facilities or accounts at the Agriculture Bank of China, they will
not be allowed to purchase grain.
</P>
<P>
Financial departments should promptly allocate sufficient funds
to subsidize interest payments and fees for provincial grain
reserves.
</P>
<P>
State-owned grain companies should publish the purchasing price
and quality standards, and to pay sellers in cash immediately and
sell the grain at a price that will be slightly higher than the
cost.
</P>
<P>
The Central Government attaches great importance to improving
the grain distribution system. On a national televised conference
on June 3, Premier Zhu Rongji emphasized that all surplus grain
should be purchased at protective prices, that state-owned grain
enterprises must sell grain for a slight profit, and that grain
funds must be used properly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
