<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four-Way Talks on Unemployment in Southern Italy Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government opened here
Thursday consultations with the country's biggest trade union
confederations, employers and local authorities on ways to tackle
the thorny issue of unemployment in southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
In an address to open the consultations, Prime Minister Romano
Prodi said the four-partite talks are intended to assess the
impact of government decisions already made and "identify the
limitations and procedural bottlenecks," the ANSA news agency
reported without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the talks are a large government delegation
led by Prodi, the biggest three trade union confederations of
CGIL, CISL and UIL, a delegation from the Confindustria employers
confederation as well as southern mayors and regional presidents.
</P>
<P>
Prodi proposed the formation of three working groups at the
national level.
</P>
<P>
One will be given the job of checking and monitoring the system
of incentives and facilitations. Another will analyze
bureaucratic procedures for authorizations and the third will
study the issues connected to illegal "black jobs" and socially
useful work schemes.
</P>
<P>
Southern Italy has the highest rate of unemployment in Italy,
with 2.8 million people, or 22 percent of the population in the
region, out of work. Nationally, the unemployment rate stands at
12 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to latest data released by Italy's National
Statistics Institute, the unemployment rate peaked at 25 percent
in the southernmost mainland region of Calabria in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
