<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan net foreign debt was 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars in the first quarter of this year, 65 million dollars
less than that at the end of 1997, Uruguay's Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The fall was attributed to the increase of international
reserves in the official banking system. These reserves rose from
about 2.8 billion dollars in December 1997 to about 2.9 billion
dollars in March.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Argentine industrial output grew about 6
percent in May, compared with last May.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the construction industry was 5 percent more in
the first five months of this year than the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Revenues from customs taxes increased 17 million
dollars in the first four months of this year, compared with the
same period of 1997, as a result of lowerer tariffs.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian government set 13.47 billion dollars
as the minimum price for the sale of 12 state enterprises of the
Telebras System (Telecommunicaciones Brasilenas, S.A.).
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Communications Minister Luiz Carlos Mendonca de
Barros said that the sale will be officially announced on July 29.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Brazilian government can get a total
of 32.87 billion dollars from the sales.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica will build a new geothermal energy plant
with a 49.35 million dollar loan from the Interamerican
Development Bank (IADB).
</P>
<P>
This station, Miravalles III, will have a generating capacity
of 17 megawatts. It will be built through the new mode of
construction, operation and transfer.
</P>
<P>
The plant, located at Guayabo de Bagaces of Guanacaste, 150
kilometers north of San Jose, will start operation in 2000.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican international reserves decreased 49
million dollars in May 29-June 5 and the Bank of Mexico's net
international assets dropped 213 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombian coffee price has dropped to the
lowest level this year when it closed at 1.37 dollars per pound in
the New York Stock Market Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian grain closed at 1.47 dollars per pound last month.
</P>
<P>
Colombia had previously planned to export 11 million to 11.2
million 60-kilo bags of coffee, but the figure fell to 10.2
million due to the negative impact of the "El Nino" phenomenon.
</P>
</TEXT>
