<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Armed Forces to Maintain Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Any action threatening political
and social stability in the reform process in Indonesia would not
be tolerated, local press Friday quoted The Armed Forces' (ABRI's)
Commander Wiranto as saying.
</P>
<P>
"ABRI's political stance toward the reform process is very
clear and firm. The reform process must be constitutional,
consistent, in the right direction, peaceful and orderly," Wiranto
said in his report to President B.J. Habibie during a ceremony at
the Presidential Palace here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He warned that unruly demonstrations and protests in the
country would be crushed.
</P>
<P>
"The commotion of political activity, the various statements
and demonstrations, if they are allowed to continue, they can
disrupt stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Habibie also shared the view that
prolonged street demonstrations and the occupation of several
government offices could destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
"If this reform wave becomes uncontrollable and violates the
foundations which unite our very pluralistic nation, it could be
possible that our nation will become divided and weak," the
President said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to face a national disintegration as
experienced by other nations," Habibie added.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony, the first official meeting between the President
and ABRI's Commander since Habibie replaced Soeharto last month,
was attended by 151 senior officers from the rank of colonel to
four-star general.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after the ceremony, Wiranto reaffirmed
that ABRI had supported the constitutional government under
President Habibie since the beginning of the new administration.
</P>
<P>
He urged the nation to give the current government an
opportunity to settle the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The nation needs political stability and a conducive
environment to get out of the crisis," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
