<HEADLINE> Laid-off Textile Workers Creating New Jobs For Themselves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Textile workers in the city of
Suzhou, in east China's Jiangsu Province, who were laid off, have
created new jobs for themselves by using the old facilities of
bankrupt companies to set up entirely new ventures.
</P>
<P>
With the assistance of the local government, unemployed textile
workers in the city have set up five self-help enterprises, which
provide more than 200 jobs as well as 10,000 yuan in income
annually for each worker.
</P>
<P>
The Suzhou Textile Re-employment Center rented several
workshops from the Suzhou Towel Factory, spent 80,000 yuan, and
brought in four technicians, creating the first enterprise
for the city's unemployed workers.
</P>
<P>
The new company produces toys that are proving very popular in
the United States and Europe, and it employs 50 people who were
laid-off. Its annual production is worth 12 million yuan and it
has profits of 800,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The unemployed textile workers have also set up a garment
factory, a knitting mill, and other enterprises, creating not only
new jobs but also a lot more money for themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
