<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Truck Sales Plunge in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Trucks sold by the Philippines'
assemblers in May 1998 dropped by 53.2 percent to just 3,340 units
from the year-ago level of 7,146 units due to the lingering
effects of the Asian financial crisis, according to an industry
report.
</P>
<P>
In the report published Friday, the Chamber of Automotive
Manufacturers of the Philippines Inc. (Campi) said last month's
commercial vehicle or truck sales brought to just 6,291 units the
number of vehicles, including cars, sold in May.
</P>
<P>
The number of vehicles sold last month represented a 54.2
percent drop when compared to the 13,749 vehicles sold for the
corresponding month last year.
</P>
<P>
Campi officials identified four reasons for the auto sales
slump -- high interest rates, increased prices, increased down
payment requirements and banks' reluctance to increase auto loans.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi emerged as the country's top commercial vehicle
brand, but truck sales of Mitsubishi Motors Phils. Corp. for May
dropped 36.7 percent to just 919 units from 1,452 for the
corresponding month last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
