<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Most U.S. Community Playgrounds Lack Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A study released Thursday
indicates that most U.S. community playgrounds lack safety, which
result in hundreds of thousands of injuries each year.
</P>
<P>
The study, released by the Consumer Federation of America and
the U.S. Public Interest Research Group, found that nine out of
ten playgrounds surveyed had inadequate protective surfaces.
</P>
<P>
The results came from a nationwide survey of 760 playgrounds in
24 states.
</P>
<P>
"Kids are going to scrape their knees, try risk-taking
behavior," said Mary Ellen Fise, Product safety director of the
Consumer Federation of American, adding that one reason behind the
problem is that "playground equipment is not cheap.'
</P>
<P>
Each year, about 150,000 children sustain playground injuries
that require trips to hospitals. About 15 children die.
</P>
<P>
The study, done every two years since 1992, recommended a
number of guidelines for improvement of playground safety,
including protective surfaces and climbing equipment with top rung
or platform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
