<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's No.1 Arts, Crafts Workshop to Reopen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Arts and Craft World,
considered the No.1 arts and crafts workshop in China, is expected
to re-open at its original site on the bustling Wangfujing Street
in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was closed three years ago for renovation and
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Its predecessor was the Beijing Arts and Crafts Service Center,
which opened in 1954.
</P>
<P>
For a long period of time, the workshop served as the only
supplier of gifts of top Party and state leaders for overseas
visits.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1950s, with the support of the government, the
workshop shouldered the task of reviving the dying traditional
Chinese artworks through providing funds and management personnel,
and collecting and purchasing related artworks.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the art of making famous products such as pottery
and porcelain products made at Jingdezhen, in east China's Jiangxi
Province, and red-brown pottery pots made in Yixing, in east China's
Jiangsu Province, were saved and put into batch production.
</P>
<P>
This art shop organized exhibitions of artworks in nine Eastern
European countries, thus opening the doors for the export of
Chinese artworks.
</P>
<P>
Artworks the shops sells cover 70 categories in nearly 20,000
varieties, such as pearls, jewels and jade ware, facial makeup,
clay figurines, the four treasures of the study (writing brush,
inkstick, inkslab and paper), papercuts and applique.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the earthquake which hit Tangshan in north China's
Hebei Province, in 1976, the art shop's building was listed as a
"dangerous building".
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, the Beijing Arts and Crafts Group began
rebuilding the shop, with an investment of 300 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to the group's general manager, Wang Zhen, the
newly-completed 32,000-sq-m Beijing Arts and Crafts World,
which occupies 13 floors, is expected to be a center for shopping,
catering, entertainment and handling official business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian President Cancels Trips to Lebanon, Cape Verde </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso has canceled plans to visit Lebanon and
Cape Verde ahead of the October presidential elections, the Jornal
do Brazil newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said Cardoso made the decision so he could
concentrate on domestic affairs after his return from the United
States, where he attended the United Nations anti-drug meeting.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso had planned to visit Lebanon in July and travel to Cape
Verde in September to take part in a presidential summit of
Portuguese-speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the Brazilian Foreign Ministry, Vice-President
Marco Maciel will attend Cape Verde summit on behalf of Cardoso.
</P>
</TEXT>
