<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Historical Trend on Healthy Growth of Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin had
a successful state visit to the United States last fall, marking
the advent of a new era in Sino-U.S. relations. Amidst the sound
and stable growth of Sino-U.S. relations, the U.S. House of
Representatives, disregarding the consistent stance of the Chinese
government and the commitment by every U.S. administration after
1972, approved a motion last Tuesday in which it required
President Bill Clinton during his upcoming China visit to impose
pressure on the country and force it to abandon non-peaceful means
for the liberation of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
This is not only a bold move which interferes in China's
internal affairs but also sets barriers against further developing
the improved Sino-U.S. relationship.
</P>
<P>
It goes without saying that the Taiwan issue, the most
important and sensitive problem in Sino-U.S. relations, will be
an unavoidable topic during the Sino-U.S. summit between Jiang
and Clinton due later this month.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Sino-U.S. Joint Statement signed by the two heads
of state at the previous Washington summit has already
demonstrated the basic stance of the two governments in this
regard. The Chinese side in the statement underlined that the key
to healthy and stable Sino-U.S. ties is to properly handle the
Taiwan issue in accordance with the three joint communiques signed
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The American side reiterated that the U.S. side adheres to "One
China" stand and observes the three communiques. President Clinton
and the U.S. government also clearly elaborated that the United
States did not support "Two Chinas" or "One China, One Taiwan",
nor the independence of Taiwan, or Taiwan's entry into the United
Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Historical Trend on Healthy Growth of Sino-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Chinese government has repeatedly announced its willingness
to reunify the country by peaceful means, but cannot undertake not
to use armed means to resolve the Taiwan issue. The stance of the
Chinese government in this regard is targeted at foreign
interference and so-called "Taiwan independence" instead of the
Taiwan people.
</P>
<P>
It is the set guideline for reunifying China by peaceful
means. However, every sovereign state has the right to take all
means it deems essential, including military means, to safeguard
its national sovereignty and territorial integration. On how to
handle its internal affairs, the Chinese government is not obliged
to make any commitment to any foreign country or any party,
especially those aiming to split China.
</P>
<P>
Many far-sighted people in the U.S. hold that Sino-US relations
would be stalled, and even see some setbacks if the Taiwan issue
is beset with troubles. Such a move is itself not in the realistic
and long-term interests of the U.S. They suggest that the U.S. look
squarely at China's position on the Taiwan question, effectively
observe the Sino-U.S. joint communiques and Sino-US Joint
Statement as well as the commitment made by the U.S. government,
so as to maintain the good momentum of development in Sino-US ties.
</P>
<P>
Only by dispelling all interference and uproar in Sino-US
relations can statesmen in both countries stand higher and see
farther in dealing with Sino-US relations, as a reformer in
China's Song Dynasty said in a poem: "Unafraid of floating clouds
blocking the view, because you stand at the pinnacle." And only by
grasping the fundamental interests of the people of both countries
and having an overall world situation in mind can a prosperous,
stable and peaceful world be properly brought into the 21st
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sole Tropical Rain Forest Near Tropic of Cancer Under Protection (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The tropical rain forest accounts for eight percent of the total
area of the Xishuangbanna Nature Reserve.
</P>
<P>
"The government has made great efforts to build the nature
reserve and offered a guarantee for the effective survival of the
tropical rain forest," said Li Hongwei, who is also an engineer with
the Yunnan Provincial Design Institute of Forestry Survey and
Planning.
</P>
<P>
The first nature reserve was established on 57,000 ha of land
in Xishuangbanna as early as in 1959, he said, and after nearly
four decades it has grown to more than 240,000 ha and contains
most of the rain forest.
</P>
<P>
The nature reserve is divided into a core area and an
experimental area. The core area is exclusively for farming
activities, while the scale of farmland is under strict control
in the experimental area. Hunting is banned in all areas of the
nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
In order to stop farmers from cutting trees for residential
buildings and fuel use, the local government has designated a
commercial forest area beyond the nature reserve, and executes
planned felling.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the use of new building materials relieves the
burden on the nature reserve. The traditional bamboo houses in
which the local people live are being replaced by brick and cement
buildings.
</P>
<P>
The local government is now carrying out a resettlement
program, gradually removing itinerant farmers from the rain
forest. In 1997 the government spent more than four million yuan
(about 480,000 US dollars) building new villages for over 3,000
farmers of the Yao and Hani minority nationalities who had moved
from the rain forest.
</P>
<P>
A Norwegian prince, when visiting Xishuangbanna, insisted on
taking a look at the tropical rain forest. When he saw the
thriving trees there, he said that he had seen an example of
successful protection of nature.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sole Tropical Rain Forest Near Tropic of Cancer under Protection (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Xishuangbanna
Nature Reserve, which mainly features protection of a tropical
rain forest, has been enlarged to 247,000 ha from 242,000 ha in the
past 15 years, according to a recent survey by the UN Global
Environment Facility.
</P>
<P>
Li Hongwei, chief of the UN survey program, said that this
indicates that "China has worked hard to protect the sole tropical
rain forest near the Tropic of Cancer by establishing a nature
reserve."
</P>
<P>
The tropical rain forest, located in the Xishuangbanna Dai
Autonomous Prefecture and the adjacent areas in southwestern
Yunnan Province, is the sole tropical rain forest left near the
Tropic of Cancer, and it is also the one at the highest latitude
on earth. Other areas on the same latitude are mostly
desertified.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Han Xingguo, a research fellow with the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, attributed the survival of the tropical rain forest in
Xishuangbanna to its unique geographical location.
</P>
<P>
The Himalayas, which acts as a natural protective screen,
hinder the invasion of cold air, while warm, moist air from the
Indian Ocean brings plentiful rain for the forest, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Xishuangbanna has at least 4,900 species of higher plants,
including 58 rare and endangered ones that have been put under
state protection. It is also home to a quarter of the species of
mammals and a third of species of birds in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina to Host FTAA Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Argentina will host a
committee meeting of the Free Trade Agreement of the Americas
(FTAA) from June 16 to 18, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Campbell, the international economic relations secretary,
told a press conference that there will be nine groups of
negotiations. They will deal with such subjects as competence,
subsidies, anti-dumping and compensatory rights.
</P>
<P>
There will also be four consultative groups -- on small
economies, electronic commerce and facilitation of business.
</P>
<P>
Campbell said the groups must agree on a timetable for
negotiations in their areas, and consider the links between
themselves.
</P>
<P>
They will also have to identify the principles that will guide
the talks, and the means of reaching targets agreed on during the
Costa Rica Ministerial Declaration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
