<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Surges to Eight-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar surged more than
2.3 yen to approach an eight-year high against the Japanese
currency in a broad rally Thursday, being stimulated by U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin's comments on the yen's weakness.
</P>
<P>
Traders interpreted Rubin's remarks as a sign there would be no
coordinated international action to support the yen.
</P>
<P>
In its advance, the dollar climbed to a record against the
Canadian dollar and the Mexican peso while jumping against the
German mark.
</P>
<P>
The dollar ended at 143.79 yen in late New York trading, up
from 141.43 yen Wednesday. At one point during the trading, the
dollar rose to 143.97 yen, a level never seen since September 4,
1990.
</P>
<P>
For the past few weeks, the dollar has pushed past several
seven-year highs against yen, but didn't trade higher because of
fears of intervention.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was changing hands at 1.8087 marks in New York,
up from 1.7962 Wednesday. During trading, it hit 1.8095 marks, a
level last seen in late April.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian dollar fell below 68 U.S. cents for the first time
in its 140-year history, dropping as low was 67.98 cents before
settling in New York at even 68 cents, down from 68.22 cents
Wednesday. The previous low of 68.10 cents was reached in January.
</P>
<P>
Canada's economy has suffered because of the plight of Asia,
one of its major markets for coal, lumber and minerals.
</P>
<P>
The peso's fall was accompanied by a 2.4 percent drop in
Mexico's key stock index.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday: 1.4965 Swiss francs, up from 1.4870; 6.0675 French
francs, up from 6.0220; and 1,781.00 Italian lire, up from
1,768.00.
</P>
<P>
The British pound fell to 1.6273 U.S. dollars from 1.6289 U.S.
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
