<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Assists Armenia to Improve Yerevan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Thursday
approved an interest-free credit of equivalent to 30 million U.S.
dollars to Armenia for a Municipal Development Project to help
improve water supply in Yerevan.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to improve the management and delivery of
water and wastewater services for the Yerevan area, while laying
the groundwork for the involvement of the private sector in these
services.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be provided by the International Development
Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessional lending wing for
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Since Armenia joined the World Bank in 1992, and IDA in 1993,
IDA commitments to the country have totalled some 384.8 million
dollars for 16 projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Disarmament Hears Joint Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Conference on Disarmament heard
Thursday a joint declaration by the foreign ministers of eight
countries on nuclear disarmament after the nuclear tests conducted
by India and Pakistan last month.
</P>
<P>
In the joint declaration issued on June 9, the foreign
ministers of Brazil, Egypt, Ireland, Mexico, New Zealand,
Slovenia, South Africa and Sweden suggested that the
nuclear-weapon states should immediately abandon present
hair-trigger postures by proceeding to deactivating their nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
They said that non-strategic nuclear weapons should also be
removed from deployed sites. They believed that such measures
would create beneficial conditions for continued disarmament
efforts and help prevent inadvertent, accidental or unauthorized
launches.
</P>
<P>
The Conference on Disarmament had debated in length the recent
nuclear tests carried out by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers said the continued threat to humanity
represented by the perspective of the indefinite possession of
nuclear weapons had been further underscored by the nuclear tests
conducted by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
They also said that the three nuclear-weapon-capable states,
India, Israel and Pakistan, must also clearly and urgently reverse
the pursuit of their respective nuclear weapons development or
deployment and refrain from any actions which could undermine the
efforts of the international community on nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
The Conference on Disarmament resumes its plenary on June 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC Makers Try to Slip Grasp of Intel, Microsoft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Major personal computer makers of
the United States are announcing a series of moves showing their
wills of independence of the control of Intel or Microsoft, the
two PC giants in the world.
</P>
<P>
The USA Today reported Thursday that half of the 10 major PC
makers now use lower-cost chips from Intel rivals in some PCs,
as a way to stay outside of Intel's stronghold.
</P>
<P>
Compaq, the biggest PC maker, said this week that it will sell
home PCs this fall that have four keyboard buttons to quickly take
users to Internet portal sites, such as Yahoo, on-line stores,
search services and electronic mail -- bypassing Microsoft's
control of the Windows desktop.
</P>
<P>
Hewlett Packard has already offered new keyboards with such
buttons.
</P>
<P>
Packard Bell-NEC announced it will offer PCs that have screen
icons, placed outside Microsoft's Windows desktop screen and
thus outside of Microsoft's control, that link users to Internet
sites, including on-line stores.
</P>
<P>
Gateway recently won Microsoft'a approval to direct customers
to Gateway's Internet service provider (ISP) as opposed to those
sanctioned by Microsoft. That means more revenue for Gateway,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Dell Computer expects to tout its own group of ISPs in
upcoming PCs, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts by the PC makers are designed to offset
declining PC prices, slowing growth and shrinking margins, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
It also said that of vital importance to PC makers is finding
a way to cash in on the growth of the digital economy -- the
buying of goods and services over the Internet. That is
projected to be a 300 billion U.S. dollar market by 2002 as the
number of Net transactions doubles every 100 days.
</P>
<P>
So far, PC makers have done little more than supply the PC
boxes consumers use to access the digital economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personages Call for Enhancing U.S.-China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States and China
need enhanced cooperation and relations, stressed a number of
American personages prior to U.S. President Bill Clinton's state
visit to China.
</P>
<P>
They criticized some remarks meant to obstruct the development
of U.S.-China ties and block Clinton's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
They disagreed with some anti-China groups, who want to block
the development of the bilateral relations, by using such issues
as human rights, trade, technology and the issue of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The United States and China have made progress in improving
their relationship, although the progress comes hard and slowly,
but it does come, and both countries have to keep working at it,
said Representative Lee H. Hamilton, a Democrat from Indiana, in a
recent Xinhua interview.
</P>
<P>
"President Bill Clinton's visit to China is very important. I
think we are seeking to place the U.S.-China relationship on a
more normal basis, a more solid footing," said Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
On MFN status for China, the Representative said it will
eventually be approved but it will go through a "rocky process,
a difficult process."
</P>
<P>
The MFN is a very important symbol of the U.S.-China relationship,
he said. "If we were to defeat the MFN treatment to China, it
would send a huge signal of deterioration of the U.S.-China
relationship.
</P>
<P>
"I don't like the MFN debate every year, I think it
exacerbates, it makes more difficult the U.S.-China relationship.
I wish we could get rid of the debate," Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
But in the process there is a lot of anti-China rhetoric that
makes the management of the relationship more difficult, he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the rhetoric in Congress about China as "very
confusing," Hamilton said, "I think a lot of it has to be
understood in terms of American politics. There are lot of people
who oppose President Clinton and they are using the China policy
as a means of attacking him politically and attacking the
Democratic Party, even though the president's policy is the policy
of engagement which was originally established by President Nixon
and has been carried out by every president, Republican and
Democrat since the opening to China in the early 1970s," Hamilton
said.
</P>
<P>
Jeffrey E. Garten, Dean of the Yale School of Management,
pointed out in an article in the latest issue of the Business Week
that it would be a shame if the frenzy over satellite in Congress
undercut or even forced the postponement of President Clinton's
summit, the best opportunity in a decade to build constructive
ties between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Since last October, when China's President Jiang Zemin came to
Washington, the Administration has emphasized expanding American
business dealings with China, he said. "It has attempted to keep
any one issue from throwing the U.S.-China relationship off
course."
</P>
<P>
"It has tried to cultivate China as a partner rather than make
it feel like the enemy. These were exactly the right goals," he
added.
</P>
<P>
For its part, he noted, China has acted responsibly in
putting Asia's -- and America's -- economic interests above its
own in not devaluing the Renminbi, and help defuse the threat of
nuclear war between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the lack of understanding about the fundamentals
of the bilateral relationship, and too much uninformed rhetoric,
Brent Scowcroft, former U.S. Presidential National Security
Advisor, said, "More than 25 years after the signing of the
Shanghai Communique, I doubt that half of the Members of the U.S.
Congress can explain the document."
</P>
<P>
On the alleged missile technology transfer to China, Robert A.
Kapp, President of the U.S.-China Business Council, said, "I find
the whole thing regrettable and we, as business community, are
very concerned about the casual acceptance of the allegations as
the facts."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope Clinton's China visit would help increase
mutual understanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges 160 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
sank nearly 160 points Thursday as a soaring dollar compounded
concerns about the impact of the Asian financial crisis on U.S.
companies.
</P>
<P>
The Dow plunged 159.93 to 8,811.77, and has now lost more than
250 points in three sessions, essentially wiping out the sharp
gain of the three sessions before that.
</P>
<P>
Broader indexes also dropped despite a strong bond market,
where interest rates fell to an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign exchange market here, the U.S. dollar soared to
its highest level against the Japanese yen since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The dollar surged after Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin,
speaking before a Senate committee, appeared to rule out a U.S.
role in supporting the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
The Dow now sits 400 points below May 13's record close of
9,211.84, but still holds a gain of 900 points, or more than 11
percent, for the year.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 17.70 to 1,094.58, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 23.50 to 1,749.75.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-3 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 734.78 million
shares, slightly above Wednesday's tally of 733.36 million.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 8.87 to 565.50, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 7.80 to 699.05.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.73 to 444.35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
