<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's UN Ambassador on His Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has made the
decision on moratorium on nuclear testing because it remains
committed to the concept of the nuclear disarmament and nuclear
non-proliferation in South Asia, Ahmad Kamal, Pakistan's
Ambassador to the United Nations said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kamal was responding to the announcement made by the Government
of Pakistan this morning on a unilateral moratorium on nuclear
testing.
</P>
<P>
Kamal said Pakistan has invited U.N. Secretary-General to visit
Pakistan, and hopefully to visit India also, because Pakistan
believes that the matter of the tension in South Asia and the
nuclearization of South Asia are matters of primary importance.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said since it is the duty of the
Secretary-General to enter the matters to the Security Council and
to remove the threat to peace and security, it is absolutely
necessary for him to engage and to involve personally
in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said the Secretary-General has decided that he wants
initially to send a personal envoy to South Asia, and
Pakistan welcomes the move and hopes that the envoy will come
urgently as early as the beginning of the next week.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador expressed the hope the visit by the envoy will
pave the way for the visit by the Secretary-General himself
and defuse the tension in South Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Opposes Mexico's Prosecuting U.S. Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said Thursday that prosecution of U.S. agents
accused of violating Mexican law in an anti-drug sting operation
in Mexico would be counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Albright said that Washington
will cooperate "as possible," but said prosecution and extradition
of American agents would be counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
Albright's comments raised the possibility of a conflict with
Mexican authorities, which is preparing to accuse the U.S. agents
of a series of violations while in Mexico carrying out "Operation
Casablanca."
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government reacted angrily after learning that the
presence of U.S. undercover agents had been concealed from Mexican
officials.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the news conference, Mexican Foreign Secretary
Rosario Green noted that both governments were taking steps to
improve cooperation and communication on drug enforcement.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Operation Casablanca, Green said, "The
investigation has to be pursued according to law."
</P>
<P>
Following the two days of meetings, Albright and Green decided
to install hotlines to facilitate instant communication between
them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright said that the two countries' justice
departments would begin talks soon on enhancing law enforcement
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Green criticized American behavior. "In the
absence of communication, cooperation, trust, respect and will,
our relationship runs the risk of heading down the wrong path," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
