<DOCNO> XIE19980612.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Says Britain Opposes Kosovo Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook Thursday told leader of Kosovo Albanians Ibrahim Rugova that
Britain supported peaceful solution of the current Kosovo crisis,
but was against Kosovo independence.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting Rugova, Cook said that the
British government was determined to halt the worsening crisis in
Kosovo at a meeting of the six-nation Contact Group foreign
ministers in London Friday.
</P>
<P>
"President (Slobodan) Milosevic is now on his last warning. He
would be making a heavy mistake if he imagined the international
community will be as slow to respond as it was during the
unfolding tragedy in Bosnia," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook also made it clear that the international community was
totally opposed to gaining total independence by ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"It is absolutely true the position of the Contact Group and
the international community is to support enhanced autonomy for
Kosovo, not independence," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe the Kosovo Liberation Army can liberate
their people. The risk is that they will only prolong the
suffering of their people," he added.
</P>
<P>
Early Thursday, British Prime Minister Tony Blair also held
brief talks with Rugova and promised Britain would do its best to
help resolve the Kosovo crisis peacefully.  
</P>
</TEXT>
