<HEADLINE> Ex-Im Bank Extends Export Credit Support to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Export-Import Bank on
Thursday announced to provide South Korea with up to 2.25 billion
U.S. dollars of short-and medium-term export credit support.
</P>
<P>
Under the short-term program, EX-Im Bank expects to authorize
250 million U.S. dollars in export credit insurance for South
Korean Banks, in addition to 750 million dollars it made available
in January, the bank said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
Under its medium-term program, Ex-Im Bank has agreed to make
available as much as 2 billion dollars to support exports of U.S.
capital goods and services in South Korea, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Ex-Im Bank is an independent U.S. government agency that
assists in financing the export of U.S. goods and services to
industrializing and developing markets all over the world by
providing loans, loan guarantees, and insurance.
</P>
<P>
South Korean President Kim Dae-jung is now in the United States
for nine-day visit. One of the major issues he had discussed with
U.S. President Bill Clinton on Tuesday was to secure more help for
the troubled economy in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has promised to provide further financial support to
Kim for his economic reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
