<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Says Water Scarcity Constraints Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The scarcity of water,
especially in Africa, the Middle East and Southeast Asia, is one
of world's top environmental challenges, a release from the
United Nations said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The release said a third of the world's population lives in
areas where lack of water limits development, and in 20 years,
two-thirds of the world's population will live in areas where
development is constrained because of water scarcity.
</P>
<P>
The release said lack of water can also lead to conflict over
resources and has adverse health consequences on populations.
</P>
<P>
It showed that there has been a six-fold increase in water
consumption globally this century, largely due to agricultural and
industrial activity.
</P>
<P>
It also revealed that 12 million hectares of forests are lost
every year and that 60 percent of the world's coral reefs are at
risk due to pollution and coastal development, especially in
Southeast Asia and in the Indian Ocean.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
