<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Two Parties Join Hands in Pushing Constitution Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
signed on Thursday a joint declaration on constitutional reform
with Britain's third party, the Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
The two-page declaration, signed by Blair and Liberal
Democratic Party leader Paddy Ashdown, committed both parties to
end the voting rights of hereditary peers in the House of Lords as
"the first stage in a process to create a modern second chamber".
</P>
<P>
"The Government and the Liberal Democrats will not necessarily
agree on every aspect of these and future constitutional reforms.
But we are at one on the elements of change, the vital necessity
of them, and the importance of the partnership we have created to
bring them about," the document said.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Democrats, who have 46 seats in the House of
Commons, are the most radical of Britain's three main parties on
reforming the constitution and have a long-standing commitment to
proportional representation.
</P>
<P>
Senior Liberal Democrats told reporters the declaration made it
certain there would be more constitutional changes before and
after the next election.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Labor Party and the Liberal Democrats have worked
together last year to bring in devolved parliaments for Scotland
and Wales -- changes opposed by the opposition Conservative Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
